{"title_page": "SS-GB (TV series)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2016}}\n{{EngvarB|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name = SS-GB\n| image = SS GB titlecard.JPG\n| alt = Series title over a swastika and a leaden sky of fighter planes\n| genre = {{ubl | [[Alternative history]] | [[Thriller (genre)|Thriller]]}}\n| creator = [[Len Deighton]]\n| based_on = {{Based on|''[[SS-GB]]''|[[Len Deighton]]}}\n| writer = [[Neal Purvis and Robert Wade]]\n| director = [[Philipp Kadelbach]]\n| starring = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Sam Riley]]\n* [[Kate Bosworth]]\n* [[James Cosmo]]\n}}\n| composer = [[Dan Jones (composer)|Dan Jones]]\n| country = United Kingdom\n| language = English\n| num_series = 1\n| num_episodes = 5\n| executive_producer = {{Plainlist|\n* Sally Woodward Gentle\n* Lee Morris\n* Neal Purvis\n* Robert Wade\n}}\n| producer = Patrick Schweitzer\n| location = [[London]], [[England]], [[United Kingdom|UK]]\n| cinematography = Stuart Bentley\n| editor = David Blackmoore\n| runtime = 60 minutes\n| company = Sid Gentle Films Ltd\n| distributor = [[BBC Worldwide]]\n| picture_format = [[16:9]] [[1080i]]\n| audio_format = [[Stereophonic sound|Stereo]]\n| first_aired = {{Start date|2017|2|19|df=y}}\n| last_aired = {{End date|2017|3|19|df=y}}\n| website         = https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b08ghxqb\n| website_title   = BBC website\n| channel = [[BBC One]]\n}}\n\n'''''SS-GB''''' is a 2017 British drama series produced for the [[BBC]]<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ellis-Petersen|first1=Hannah|title=''SS-GB''{{'s}} dystopian parallel universe \u2013 a drama for our time|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2017/feb/10/ss-gb-nazi-britain-dystopian-parallel-universe-television-drama|accessdate=14 February 2017|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=10 February 2017}}</ref> and based on the 1978 [[SS-GB|novel of the same name]] by [[Len Deighton]]. It is set in a 1941 [[alternative timeline]] in which the United Kingdom is occupied by [[Nazi Germany]] during the [[Second World War]].\n\n{{TOC limit|1}}\n\n[[File:Map of Western Europe for ss-gb 2017.png|thumb|left|Europe as described in the show nine months after the [[Royal Air Force]] lost the [[Battle of Britain]] to the German [[Luftwaffe]]. The southern part of Great Britain is controlled by the German Reich while the northern part is an unoccupied zone, even though there is still conflict in the area.]]\n==Plot==\nIn this [[Alternate history|alternative world]], it is November 1941, nine months after a successful [[Operation Sea Lion|German invasion of the UK]]. [[Winston Churchill]] has been executed, and King [[George VI]] is a prisoner who has not been seen in public for some time. [[Queen Elizabeth The Queen Mother|His wife]] and daughters [[Elizabeth II|Elizabeth]] and [[Princess Margaret, Countess of Snowdon|Margaret]] escaped. A UK [[government in exile]] led by [[Conolly Abel Smith|Rear-Admiral Conolly]] exists but is not recognised by the [[United States]]. [[Nazi Germany|Germany]] has also maintained [[Germany\u2013Soviet Union relations before 1941|friendly relations]] with the [[Soviet Union]], and [[Vyacheslav Molotov|Soviet Foreign Minister Molotov]] has just flown in to oversee the removal of the body of [[Karl Marx]] to the Soviet Union.\n\nDouglas Archer, a [[Scotland Yard]] murder squad detective with a stellar reputation, is working under a German superior from the ''[[Schutzstaffel]]'' (SS), the security force of the [[Nazi Party]]. Though his wife was killed by a [[The Blitz|German bombing raid]], Archer avoids involvement in political crime and views resistance to the Nazi Empire as futile. A routine murder investigation becomes political when it appears to have been perpetrated by agents of the Resistance movement. An aggressive SS officer arrives and takes control of the investigation, which is of interest to the SS because the victim may have possessed data from the German army's programme to produce an [[Nuclear weapon|atomic bomb]]. Archer also learns that his secretary and lover Sylvia Manning is a member of the Resistance, and he is reluctantly drawn into a conspiracy against the Germans.\n\n== Production ==\nIn November 2014, it was announced that the BBC had commissioned writers [[Neal Purvis and Robert Wade]] to adapt [[Len Deighton|Len Deighton's]] novel ''[[SS-GB]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://variety.com/2014/tv/news/james-bond-writers-to-adapt-len-deighton-novel-ss-gb-for-bbc-1201360211/ |title=James Bond Writers to Adapt Len Deighton Novel ''SS-GB'' for BBC |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date= 19 November 2014  |accessdate=17 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2015, it was announced that [[Sam Riley]] was in talks to star in the lead role of Detective Superintendent Douglas Archer of Scotland Yard.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://deadline.com/2015/08/sam-riley-neil-purvis-robert-wade-james-bond-spectre-007-ss-gb-sally-woodward-gentle-sid-gentle-downton-abbey-1201495096/ | title=Sam Riley In Talks To Star, Philipp Kadelbach On Board To Direct James Bond Scribes Purvis And Wade's ''SS:GB'' |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] | date= 7 August 2015 |accessdate=17 November 2015}}</ref> Riley's casting was confirmed in late September 2015.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2015-09-29/maleficent-and-control-star-sam-riley-to-play-the-lead-in-new-bbc-nazi-thriller-ssgb |title=Maleficent and Control star Sam Riley to play the lead in new BBC Nazi thriller ''SS:GB'' |work=[[Radio Times]] |date= 29 September 2015 |accessdate=17 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nProduction began in October 2015 and ended in January 2016. The series was produced by Sid Gentle Films Ltd. It was broadcast on [[BBC One]] in five one-hour episodes, between 19 February 2017 and 19 March 2017.\n\nThe series filmed various scenes for episodes one to four at the [[Chatham Historic Dockyard]] in Kent. The location was used as a double for London streets and the mortuary that featured in episode one.<ref>{{cite web|author=Kent Film Office|url=http://kentfilmoffice.co.uk/tag/ss-gb/|title=Kent Film Office ''SS-GB'' Article}}</ref>\n\n== Cast ==\n* [[Sam Riley]] as Detective Superintendent Douglas Archer,<ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/corporate2/mediacentre/latestnews/2015/ss-gb|title=Sam Riley and Kate Bosworth take the lead in ambitious new BBC One Drama ''SS-GB'' |publisher=[[BBC]] |date=7 October 2015 |accessdate=21 November 2015}}</ref> a Scotland Yard detective in German-occupied London\n* [[Kate Bosworth]] as Barbara Barga,<ref name=\"BBC\"/> an American reporter\n* [[Rainer Bock]] as ''[[Gruppenf\u00fchrer]]'' Fritz Kellermann,<ref name=\"BBC\"/> the SS officer supervising the police force\n* [[Aneurin Barnard]] as Police Constable Jimmy Dunn,<ref name=\"BBC\"/> a junior policeman working with Archer\n* [[Christina Cole]] as Joyce Sheenan,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.radiotimes.com/news/2017-06-09/meet-the-cast-of-ss-gb/4/|title=Meet the cast of ''SS-GB''|page=4|website=Radio Times|date=9 June 2017|accessdate=19 July 2018}}</ref> Archer's neighbour who cares for his son, and whose own husband is a prisoner of war\n* [[Maeve Dermody]] as Sylvia Manning,<ref name=\"BBC\"/> Archer's secretary and lover\n* [[Lars Eidinger]] as ''[[Standartenf\u00fchrer]]'' Oskar Huth,<ref name=\"BBC\"/> an SS officer newly-arrived in London\n* [[James Cosmo]] as Detective Sergeant Harry Woods,<ref name=\"BBC\"/> Archer's friend and co-worker\n* [[Jason Flemyng]] as Colonel George Mayhew,<ref name=\"BBC\"/> a British aristocrat\n* [[James Northcote (actor)|James Northcote]] as Dr John Spode,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/proginfo/2017/08/ss-gb|title=BBC - ''SS-GB'' - Media Centre|publisher=BBC}}</ref> an atomic physicist working with the Resistance\n* [[Sam Kronis]] as [[Heinrich Himmler]]\n{{clear}}\n\n==Episodes==\n{{Episode table |background=#9F260E |overall=|series=|title=|director=|writer= |airdate=  |viewers=|viewersR=<ref name=\"barb.co.uk\">{{cite web|url=http://www.barb.co.uk/whats-new/weekly-top-30?_s=4 |title=Weekly Top 30 Programmes |publisher=Barb.co.uk |date= }} (Search relevant dates for figures.)</ref> |country=UK  |episodes=\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 1\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 1\n| Title           = Episode 1\n| DirectedBy      = [[Philipp Kadelbach]]\n| WrittenBy       = [[Neal Purvis and Robert Wade]]\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2017|2|19|df=y}}\n| Viewers         = 8.68\n| ShortSummary    = Detective Superintendent Douglas Archer is looking into a routine murder in German-occupied London when SS officer Oskar Huth arrives and assumes control of the investigation. Archer learns that his secretary and lover Sylvia Manning is involved with the Resistance movement against the Nazis.\n| LineColor       = 9F260E\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 2\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 2\n| Title           = Episode 2\n| DirectedBy      = Philipp Kadelbach\n| WrittenBy       = Neal Purvis and Robert Wade\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2017|2|26|df=y}}\n| Viewers         = 5.54\n| ShortSummary    = Archer and Huth foil a plot by the Resistance to abduct Archer's son for leverage. Archer later lets Sylvia escape again. He is approached by a cabal of British gentlemen who appear to be conspiring against the Germans, and goes home with American reporter Barbara Barga. Barbara warns Archer not to refuse to co-operate with the Resistance, or they may kill him. Archer deduces that his murder victim William Spode was an atomic physicist working for a German faction outside the SS, presumably killed by the Resistance. Police Constable Jimmy Dunn is murdered by Resistance vigilantes who believe he has collaborated with the Nazis.\n| LineColor       = 9F260E\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 3\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 3\n| Title           = Episode 3\n| DirectedBy      = Philipp Kadelbach\n| WrittenBy       = Neal Purvis and Robert Wade\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2017|3|5|df=y}}\n| Viewers         = 4.30\n| ShortSummary    = A Resistance operative tries to kill Archer, who is later interrogating Spode's brother John when the man dies by cyanide capsule. George Mayhew and General von Ruff are plotting to rescue King George from Nazi captivity as a means for the German army to discredit the SS. Archer finds a film canister left behind by William Spode, and has its contents developed in secret. The Resistance detonates a bomb at a German-Russian ceremony to remove Karl Marx's body to the Soviet Union.\n| LineColor       = 9F260E\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 4\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 4\n| Title           = Episode 4\n| DirectedBy      = Philipp Kadelbach\n| WrittenBy       = Neal Purvis and Robert Wade\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2017|3|12|df=y}}\n| Viewers         = 3.79\n| ShortSummary    = Archer sends his son out of the city to the unoccupied zone. Harry Woods and Sylvia are picked up as the Nazis impose martial law on London. Archer agrees to help Mayhew free the king, and entrusts Barbara with Spode's negatives, which contain images of atomic calculations. Fritz Kellermann arranges for Harry's release, and Archer shelters Sylvia at his flat. One of Mayhew's conspirators is murdered, but the rescue plan proceeds. Barbara is taken by the SS.\n| LineColor       = 9F260E\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 5\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 5\n| Title           = Episode 5\n| DirectedBy      = Philipp Kadelbach\n| WrittenBy       = Neal Purvis and Robert Wade\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2017|3|19|df=y}}\n| Viewers         = 3.54\n| ShortSummary    = Archer and Harry transport King George, who is gravely ill, but they have engine trouble and call Sylvia for aid. The US Embassy secures Barbara's release before Kellermann can interrogate her. Archer, Harry, and Sylvia flee with the king as Kellermann learns of the escape and sends men in pursuit. They are ambushed by Huth at the rendezvous point, and Sylvia and the king are killed. Working with the Resistance, the Americans attack the German atomic research centre at Bringle Sands, the king's escape being a diversion to lure the security forces away from it. Having placed all the blame on Huth, Kellermann executes him by firing squad. Archer escapes with the negatives into the countryside, with Kellermann believing him dead.\n| LineColor       = 9F260E\n}}\n}}\n\n== Reception ==\nThe series received highly positive reviews<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/ss_gb/s01/|title=''SS-GB'': Miniseries|publisher=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]}}</ref> with the Telegraph giving the series 4 out of 5 and saying that the \"alt-history thriller deserves a follow-up series\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/tv/2017/03/19/ss-gb-episode-5-review-alt-history-thriller-deserves-follow/|title=''SS-GB'', episode 5, review: alt-history thriller deserves a follow-up series|first=Jasper|last=Rees|date=19 March 2017|work=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]}}</ref> The main criticisms were predominantly regarding the sound quality and reportedly inaudible dialogue for some viewers in the first episode, which the BBC offered to \"look at\" for future episodes.<ref>{{cite web|title=''SS-GB'': BBC to 'look at' sound levels after mumbling complaints|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-39038406|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=21 February 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Matthew |last=Weaver |url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2017/feb/20/i-will-mumble-this-only-once-bbcs-new-nazi-drama-ss-gb-hit-by-dialogue-complaints |title='I will mumble this only once': BBC's Nazi drama ''SS-GB'' hit by dialogue complaints |publisher=Guardian Media Group |newspaper=The Guardian |date=19 February 2017 |accessdate=31 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe first episode achieved good overnight ratings, with over 8.5 million viewers tuning in. However, as the series went on, ratings gradually fell, with only 3.5 million watching the final episode.{{citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n\nThe review by ''[[The Guardian]]'' awarded three (out of five) stars based on a viewing of the first two episodes, commenting that the series \"holds up handsomely on the big screen, favouring film noir style over pulp content\" but adding that \"it would be helpful to see more of the minutiae of London life under the Nazis, to get some fresh air after being confined to the corridors of power\".<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/film/2017/feb/15/ss-gb-review-berlin-film-festival-bbc1-miniseries, SS-GB review \u2013 London is falling in chilling alt-history of second world war</ref>\n\nThe series was released on DVD and BD on 10 July 2018; approximately a year later, the [[Rotten Tomatoes]] site showed a Critic's Consensus of 89% favourable, commenting that \"SS-GB is a convincingly wrought slice of hypothetical history, drenched in noir style and dense with moral quandaries\".<ref>https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/ss_gb/s01</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* ''[[The Man in the High Castle (TV series)|The Man in the High Castle]]''\n* ''[[Fatherland (1994 film)|Fatherland]]''\n* ''[[Philadelphia Experiment II]]''\n* ''[[An Englishman's Castle]]''\n* [[Hypothetical Axis victory in World War II]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{BBC programme}}\n* {{IMDb title|id=4939950|title=SS-GB}}\n* {{epguides|SSGB|SS-GB}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://graemeshimmin.com/ss-gb-book-review/|title=''SS-GB'': In-depth review of the book by Len Deighton and the BBC TV miniseries|date=6 December 2017|publisher=}}\n\n{{Len Deighton}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:SS-GB (Tv Series)}}\n[[Category:2017 British television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2017 British television series endings]]\n[[Category:2010s British drama television series]]\n[[Category:Fiction set in 1941]]\n[[Category:Television series about Nazis]]\n[[Category:Television series about Nazism]]\n[[Category:Television series about World War II alternate histories]]\n[[Category:2010s British television miniseries]]\n[[Category:Dystopian television series]]\n[[Category:BBC television dramas]]\n[[Category:BBC high definition programmes]]\n[[Category:Television programmes based on British novels]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in London]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2016}}\n{{EngvarB|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name = SS-GB\n| image = SS GB titlecard.JPG\n| alt = Series title over a swastika and a leaden sky of fighter planes\n| genre = {{ubl | [[Alternative history]] | [[Thriller (genre)|Thriller]]}}\n| creator = [[Len Deighton]]\n| based_on = {{Based on|''[[SS-GB]]''|[[Len Deighton]]}}\n| writer = [[Neal Purvis and Robert Wade]]\n| director = [[Philipp Kadelbach]]\n| starring = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Sam Riley]]\n* [[Kate Bosworth]]\n* [[James Cosmo]]\n}}\n| composer = [[Dan Jones (composer)|Dan Jones]]\n| country = United Kingdom\n| language = English\n| num_series = 1\n| num_episodes = 5\n| executive_producer = {{Plainlist|\n* Sally Woodward Gentle\n* Lee Morris\n* Neal Purvis\n* Robert Wade\n}}\n| producer = Patrick Schweitzer\n| location = [[London]], [[England]], [[United Kingdom|UK]]\n| cinematography = Stuart Bentley\n| editor = David Blackmoore\n| runtime = 60 minutes\n| company = Sid Gentle Films Ltd\n| distributor = [[BBC Worldwide]]\n| picture_format = [[16:9]] [[1080i]]\n| audio_format = [[Stereophonic sound|Stereo]]\n| first_aired = {{Start date|2017|2|19|df=y}}\n| last_aired = {{End date|2017|3|19|df=y}}\n| website         = https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b08ghxqb\n| website_title   = BBC website\n| channel = [[BBC One]]\n}}\n\n'''''SS-GB''''' is a 2017 British drama series produced for the [[BBC]]<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ellis-Petersen|first1=Hannah|title=''SS-GB''{{'s}} dystopian parallel universe \u2013 a drama for our time|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2017/feb/10/ss-gb-nazi-britain-dystopian-parallel-universe-television-drama|accessdate=14 February 2017|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=10 February 2017}}</ref> and based on the 1978 [[SS-GB|novel of the same name]] by [[Len Deighton]]. It is set in a 1941 [[alternative timeline]] in which the United Kingdom is occupied by [[Nazi Germany]] during the [[Second World War]].\n\n{{TOC limit|1}}\n\n[[File:Map of Western Europe for ss-gb 2017.png|thumb|left|Europe as described in the show nine months after the [[Royal Air Force]] lost the [[Battle of Britain]] to the German [[Luftwaffe]]. The southern part of Great Britain is controlled by the German Reich while the northern part is an unoccupied zone, even though there is still conflict in the area.]]\n==Plot==\nIn this [[Alternate history|alternative world]], it is November 1941, nine months after a successful [[Operation Sea Lion|German invasion of the UK]]. [[Winston Churchill]] has been executed, and King [[George VI]] is a prisoner who has not been seen in public for some time. [[Queen Elizabeth The Queen Mother|His wife]] and daughters [[Elizabeth II|Elizabeth]] and [[Princess Margaret, Countess of Snowdon|Margaret]] escaped. A UK [[government in exile]] led by [[Conolly Abel Smith|Rear-Admiral Conolly]] exists but is not recognised by the [[United States]]. [[Nazi Germany|Germany]] has also maintained [[Germany\u2013Soviet Union relations before 1941|friendly relations]] with the [[Soviet Union]], and [[Vyacheslav Molotov|Soviet Foreign Minister Molotov]] has just flown in to oversee the removal of the body of [[Karl Marx]] to the Soviet Union.\n\nDouglas Archer, a [[Scotland Yard]] homicide detective with a stellar reputation, is working under a German superior from the ''[[Schutzstaffel]]'' (SS), the security force of the [[Nazi Party]]. Though his wife was killed by a [[The Blitz|German bombing raid]], Archer avoids involvement in political crime and views resistance to the Nazi Empire as futile. A routine murder investigation becomes political when it appears to have been perpetrated by agents of the Resistance movement. An aggressive SS officer arrives and takes control of the investigation, which is of interest to the SS because the victim may have possessed data from the German army's programme to produce an [[Nuclear weapon|atomic bomb]]. Archer also learns that his secretary and lover Sylvia Manning is a member of the Resistance, and he is reluctantly drawn into a conspiracy against the Germans.\n\n== Production ==\nIn November 2014, it was announced that the BBC had commissioned writers [[Neal Purvis and Robert Wade]] to adapt [[Len Deighton|Len Deighton's]] novel ''[[SS-GB]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://variety.com/2014/tv/news/james-bond-writers-to-adapt-len-deighton-novel-ss-gb-for-bbc-1201360211/ |title=James Bond Writers to Adapt Len Deighton Novel ''SS-GB'' for BBC |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date= 19 November 2014  |accessdate=17 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2015, it was announced that [[Sam Riley]] was in talks to star in the lead role of Detective Superintendent Douglas Archer of Scotland Yard.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://deadline.com/2015/08/sam-riley-neil-purvis-robert-wade-james-bond-spectre-007-ss-gb-sally-woodward-gentle-sid-gentle-downton-abbey-1201495096/ | title=Sam Riley In Talks To Star, Philipp Kadelbach On Board To Direct James Bond Scribes Purvis And Wade's ''SS:GB'' |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] | date= 7 August 2015 |accessdate=17 November 2015}}</ref> Riley's casting was confirmed in late September 2015.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2015-09-29/maleficent-and-control-star-sam-riley-to-play-the-lead-in-new-bbc-nazi-thriller-ssgb |title=Maleficent and Control star Sam Riley to play the lead in new BBC Nazi thriller ''SS:GB'' |work=[[Radio Times]] |date= 29 September 2015 |accessdate=17 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nProduction began in October 2015 and ended in January 2016. The series was produced by Sid Gentle Films Ltd. It was broadcast on [[BBC One]] in five one-hour episodes, between 19 February 2017 and 19 March 2017.\n\nThe series filmed various scenes for episodes one to four at the [[Chatham Historic Dockyard]] in Kent. The location was used as a double for London streets and the mortuary that featured in episode one.<ref>{{cite web|author=Kent Film Office|url=http://kentfilmoffice.co.uk/tag/ss-gb/|title=Kent Film Office ''SS-GB'' Article}}</ref>\n\n== Cast ==\n* [[Sam Riley]] as Detective Superintendent Douglas Archer,<ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/corporate2/mediacentre/latestnews/2015/ss-gb|title=Sam Riley and Kate Bosworth take the lead in ambitious new BBC One Drama ''SS-GB'' |publisher=[[BBC]] |date=7 October 2015 |accessdate=21 November 2015}}</ref> a Scotland Yard detective in German-occupied London\n* [[Kate Bosworth]] as Barbara Barga,<ref name=\"BBC\"/> an American reporter\n* [[Rainer Bock]] as ''[[Gruppenf\u00fchrer]]'' Fritz Kellermann,<ref name=\"BBC\"/> the SS officer supervising the police force\n* [[Aneurin Barnard]] as Police Constable Jimmy Dunn,<ref name=\"BBC\"/> a junior policeman working with Archer\n* [[Christina Cole]] as Joyce Sheenan,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.radiotimes.com/news/2017-06-09/meet-the-cast-of-ss-gb/4/|title=Meet the cast of ''SS-GB''|page=4|website=Radio Times|date=9 June 2017|accessdate=19 July 2018}}</ref> Archer's neighbour who cares for his son, and whose own husband is a prisoner of war\n* [[Maeve Dermody]] as Sylvia Manning,<ref name=\"BBC\"/> Archer's secretary and lover\n* [[Lars Eidinger]] as ''[[Standartenf\u00fchrer]]'' Oskar Huth,<ref name=\"BBC\"/> an SS officer newly-arrived in London\n* [[James Cosmo]] as Detective Sergeant Harry Woods,<ref name=\"BBC\"/> Archer's friend and co-worker\n* [[Jason Flemyng]] as Colonel George Mayhew,<ref name=\"BBC\"/> a British aristocrat\n* [[James Northcote (actor)|James Northcote]] as Dr John Spode,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/proginfo/2017/08/ss-gb|title=BBC - ''SS-GB'' - Media Centre|publisher=BBC}}</ref> an atomic physicist working with the Resistance\n* [[Sam Kronis]] as [[Heinrich Himmler]]\n{{clear}}\n\n==Episodes==\n{{Episode table |background=#9F260E |overall=|series=|title=|director=|writer= |airdate=  |viewers=|viewersR=<ref name=\"barb.co.uk\">{{cite web|url=http://www.barb.co.uk/whats-new/weekly-top-30?_s=4 |title=Weekly Top 30 Programmes |publisher=Barb.co.uk |date= }} (Search relevant dates for figures.)</ref> |country=UK  |episodes=\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 1\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 1\n| Title           = Episode 1\n| DirectedBy      = [[Philipp Kadelbach]]\n| WrittenBy       = [[Neal Purvis and Robert Wade]]\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2017|2|19|df=y}}\n| Viewers         = 8.68\n| ShortSummary    = Detective Superintendent Douglas Archer is looking into a routine murder in German-occupied London when SS officer Oskar Huth arrives and assumes control of the investigation. Archer learns that his secretary and lover Sylvia Manning is involved with the Resistance movement against the Nazis.\n| LineColor       = 9F260E\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 2\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 2\n| Title           = Episode 2\n| DirectedBy      = Philipp Kadelbach\n| WrittenBy       = Neal Purvis and Robert Wade\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2017|2|26|df=y}}\n| Viewers         = 5.54\n| ShortSummary    = Archer and Huth foil a plot by the Resistance to abduct Archer's son for leverage. Archer later lets Sylvia escape again. He is approached by a cabal of British gentlemen who appear to be conspiring against the Germans, and goes home with American reporter Barbara Barga. Barbara warns Archer not to refuse to co-operate with the Resistance, or they may kill him. Archer deduces that his murder victim William Spode was an atomic physicist working for a German faction outside the SS, presumably killed by the Resistance. Police Constable Jimmy Dunn is murdered by Resistance vigilantes who believe he has collaborated with the Nazis.\n| LineColor       = 9F260E\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 3\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 3\n| Title           = Episode 3\n| DirectedBy      = Philipp Kadelbach\n| WrittenBy       = Neal Purvis and Robert Wade\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2017|3|5|df=y}}\n| Viewers         = 4.30\n| ShortSummary    = A Resistance operative tries to kill Archer, who is later interrogating Spode's brother John when the man dies by cyanide capsule. George Mayhew and General von Ruff are plotting to rescue King George from Nazi captivity as a means for the German army to discredit the SS. Archer finds a film canister left behind by William Spode, and has its contents developed in secret. The Resistance detonates a bomb at a German-Russian ceremony to remove Karl Marx's body to the Soviet Union.\n| LineColor       = 9F260E\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 4\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 4\n| Title           = Episode 4\n| DirectedBy      = Philipp Kadelbach\n| WrittenBy       = Neal Purvis and Robert Wade\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2017|3|12|df=y}}\n| Viewers         = 3.79\n| ShortSummary    = Archer sends his son out of the city to the unoccupied zone. Harry Woods and Sylvia are picked up as the Nazis impose martial law on London. Archer agrees to help Mayhew free the king, and entrusts Barbara with Spode's negatives, which contain images of atomic calculations. Fritz Kellermann arranges for Harry's release, and Archer shelters Sylvia at his flat. One of Mayhew's conspirators is murdered, but the rescue plan proceeds. Barbara is taken by the SS.\n| LineColor       = 9F260E\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 5\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 5\n| Title           = Episode 5\n| DirectedBy      = Philipp Kadelbach\n| WrittenBy       = Neal Purvis and Robert Wade\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2017|3|19|df=y}}\n| Viewers         = 3.54\n| ShortSummary    = Archer and Harry transport King George, who is gravely ill, but they have engine trouble and call Sylvia for aid. The US Embassy secures Barbara's release before Kellermann can interrogate her. Archer, Harry, and Sylvia flee with the king as Kellermann learns of the escape and sends men in pursuit. They are ambushed by Huth at the rendezvous point, and Sylvia and the king are killed. Working with the Resistance, the Americans attack the German atomic research centre at Bringle Sands, the king's escape being a diversion to lure the security forces away from it. Having placed all the blame on Huth, Kellermann executes him by firing squad. Archer escapes with the negatives into the countryside, with Kellermann believing him dead.\n| LineColor       = 9F260E\n}}\n}}\n\n== Reception ==\nThe series received highly positive reviews<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/ss_gb/s01/|title=''SS-GB'': Miniseries|publisher=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]}}</ref> with the Telegraph giving the series 4 out of 5 and saying that the \"alt-history thriller deserves a follow-up series\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/tv/2017/03/19/ss-gb-episode-5-review-alt-history-thriller-deserves-follow/|title=''SS-GB'', episode 5, review: alt-history thriller deserves a follow-up series|first=Jasper|last=Rees|date=19 March 2017|work=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]}}</ref> The main criticisms were predominantly regarding the sound quality and reportedly inaudible dialogue for some viewers in the first episode, which the BBC offered to \"look at\" for future episodes.<ref>{{cite web|title=''SS-GB'': BBC to 'look at' sound levels after mumbling complaints|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-39038406|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=21 February 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Matthew |last=Weaver |url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2017/feb/20/i-will-mumble-this-only-once-bbcs-new-nazi-drama-ss-gb-hit-by-dialogue-complaints |title='I will mumble this only once': BBC's Nazi drama ''SS-GB'' hit by dialogue complaints |publisher=Guardian Media Group |newspaper=The Guardian |date=19 February 2017 |accessdate=31 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe first episode achieved good overnight ratings, with over 8.5 million viewers tuning in. However, as the series went on, ratings gradually fell, with only 3.5 million watching the final episode.{{citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n\nThe review by ''[[The Guardian]]'' awarded three (out of five) stars based on a viewing of the first two episodes, commenting that the series \"holds up handsomely on the big screen, favouring film noir style over pulp content\" but adding that \"it would be helpful to see more of the minutiae of London life under the Nazis, to get some fresh air after being confined to the corridors of power\".<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/film/2017/feb/15/ss-gb-review-berlin-film-festival-bbc1-miniseries, SS-GB review \u2013 London is falling in chilling alt-history of second world war</ref>\n\nThe series was released on DVD and BD on 10 July 2018; approximately a year later, the [[Rotten Tomatoes]] site showed a Critic's Consensus of 89% favourable, commenting that \"SS-GB is a convincingly wrought slice of hypothetical history, drenched in noir style and dense with moral quandaries\".<ref>https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/ss_gb/s01</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* ''[[The Man in the High Castle (TV series)|The Man in the High Castle]]''\n* ''[[Fatherland (1994 film)|Fatherland]]''\n* ''[[Philadelphia Experiment II]]''\n* ''[[An Englishman's Castle]]''\n* [[Hypothetical Axis victory in World War II]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{BBC programme}}\n* {{IMDb title|id=4939950|title=SS-GB}}\n* {{epguides|SSGB|SS-GB}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://graemeshimmin.com/ss-gb-book-review/|title=''SS-GB'': In-depth review of the book by Len Deighton and the BBC TV miniseries|date=6 December 2017|publisher=}}\n\n{{Len Deighton}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:SS-GB (Tv Series)}}\n[[Category:2017 British television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2017 British television series endings]]\n[[Category:2010s British drama television series]]\n[[