{"title_page": "Arca No\u00eb", "text_new": "{{italic title}}\n[[File:Arca Noe, why ark did not sink, by A. Kircher. Wellcome L0013361.jpg|thumb|Explanation of why Noah's Ark did not sink, despite its size, from ''Arca No\u00eb'']]\n[[File:Arca Noe, building the ark, by A. Kircher. Wellcome L0013357.jpg|thumb|Building the ark, in ''Arca No\u00eb'']]\n[[File:Houghton GC6 K6323 675a (A) - Optica projectio.jpg |thumb|Cutaway view of Noah's Ark, illustration from ''Arca No\u00eb''|alt=Internal view of Noah's Ark Wellcome L0032185.jpg]]\n\n'''''Arca No\u00eb''''' (\u201cNoah\u2019s Ark\u201d) was a book published in 1675 by the [[Jesuit]] scholar [[Athanasius Kircher]]. It was a study of the biblical story of [[Noah\u2019s Ark]], published by the cartographer and bookseller Johannes van Waesbergen in Amsterdam.<ref name=\"Young2007\">{{cite book|author=David Young|title=The Discovery of Evolution|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vlAJwmWWF80C&pg=PA263|date=9 August 2007|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-86803-7|page=263}}</ref><ref name=\"Library2003\">{{cite book|author=Harold B. Lee Library|title=Athanasius Kircher (1602-1680), Jesuit Scholar: An Exhibition of His Works in the Harold B. Lee Library Collections at Brigham Young University|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=29984eQF86UC&pg=PA65|year=2003|publisher=Martino Publishing|isbn=978-1-57898-432-9|page=65}}</ref> Kircher's aim in ''Arca No\u00eb'' was to reconcile recent discoveries in nature and geography with the text of the Bible. This demonstration of the underlying unity and truth between revelation and science was a fundamental task of Catholic scholarship at the time.<ref name=\"DR\"/> Together with its sister volume ''Turris Babel'' (\u201c[[The Tower of Babel]]\u201d), ''Arca No\u00eb'' presented a complete intellectual project to demonstrate how contemporary science supported the account of the [[Book of Genesis]].<ref name=\"MP\"/>{{rp|61}}<ref name=\"Godwin\">{{cite book |last1=Godwin |first1=Joscelyn |title=Athanasius Kircher's Theatre of the World |date=2015 |publisher=Inner Traditions |location=Rochester, Vermont |isbn=978-1-62055-465-4}}</ref>{{rp|21}}\n\n==Structure==\nThe work was divided into three volumes: the first, ''De rebus quae ante Diluvium'', dealt with the story of Noah before the Flood, the building of the Ark, the choice of animals to go on board and how they were accommodated. The second, ''De iis, quae ipso Diluvio e jusque duratione'', concerned the Flood itself and how the Ark was managed while the flood lasted, as well as providing a mystical and allegorical explanation of its meaning, as a vessel carrying the human soul. The third volume, ''De iis, quae post Diluvium \u00e0 No\u00ebmo gesta sunt'', discussed the deeds of Noah after the Flood, compared the lands of the world as they had been before it and after, and explained how both people and animals dispersed over the globe.<ref name=\"DR\">{{cite web |last1=Dias Klautau |first1=Fabiana |last2=Roxo Beltran |first2=Maria Helena |title=Ci\u00eancia e T\u00e9cnica no livro do G\u00eaneses: a constru\u00e7\u00e3o da Arca de No\u00e9 na percep\u00e7\u00e3o do padre jesu\u00edta Athanasius Kircher (1602-1680) |url=https://www.16snhct.sbhc.org.br/resources/anais/8/1545141369_ARQUIVO_TextocompletoKlautau_Beltran_SBHC2018(rev).pdf |website=16snhct.sbhc.org.b |publisher=Semin\u00e1rio Nacional de Hist\u00f3ria da Ci\u00eancia e da Tecnologia |accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Ideas discussed==\nBy the middle of the seventeenth century, the abundance and diversity of life discovered in the [[New World]] was calling into question the previously unchallenged belief that all life on earth originated from a single point of dispersal - [[Mount Ararat]], after [[Genesis flood narrative|the Flood]]. One of the uncertainties which Kircher addressed in ''Arca No\u00eb'' was how animals had managed to colonise lands so distant across the seas. Another, to which he devoted particular attention, was how so many creatures could have fitted into the Ark at all.<ref name=\"MP\">{{cite journal |last1=Moraes dos Santos |first1=Christian Fausto |last2=Pereira Neto |first2=Juscelino |title=A natureza americana nas obras Turris Babel e Arca N\u00f6e do jesu\u00edta Athanasius Kircher|journal=Revista Brasileira de Hist\u00f3ria das Religi\u00f5es |date=May 2011 |volume=4 |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/236991808_A_natureza_americana_nas_obras_Turris_Babel_e_Arca_Noe_do_jesuita_Athanasius_Kircher_-_The_american_nature_in_the_jesuit_Athanasius_Kirchers_opuses_Turris_Babel_and_Arca_Noe/citation/download |accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref>{{rp|55-56}}                                                       \n\nKircher had first discussed the question of the size of the Ark in 1640 during a mathematical convention to celebrate the centenary of the Jesuit order. Here he delivered a technical paper on Noah's Ark, discussing the exact length of a Biblical [[cubit]].<ref name=\"Temple2006\">{{cite book|author=Nicholas Temple|title=Disclosing Horizons: Architecture, Perspective and Redemptive Space|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=deeQwGAk3aQC&pg=PA167|date=22 November 2006|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-134-11708-6|page=167}}</ref>\nIn ''Arca No\u00eb'', taking the dimensions given in the Bible, Kircher explained how it was possible that all the animals in the contemporary world could originate from a vessel of such limited size.<ref>{{cite web |title=L'Arca Noe di Athanasius Kircher (1675) |url=https://sbs.uniroma1.it/mostra/conoscenzaemisericordia/it/70/larca-noe-di-athanasius-kircher-1675 |website=sbs.uniroma1.it |publisher=Sapienza Universit\u00e0 di Roma |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> The Book of Genesis does not identify the animals taken into the Ark, describing them only as both \u201cclean\u201d and \u201cunclean\u201d. Kircher therefore speculated about which animals were aboard, how they were accommodated, and used this as a basis for working out how it could have been designed and constructed.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Phillips |first1=Amy E. |title=The Fantastic Beasts of Athanasius Kircher |url=https://www.library.georgetown.edu/woodstock/blog/fantastic-beasts-athanasius-kircher |website=library.georgetown.edu |publisher=Georgetown University |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> He also described details such as the exact year of the Flood (2396 BC), the time between the fall of the fist raindrop and Noah setting foot on dry land (365 days), where the Ark landed, and how the creatures spread over the earth after the Flood abated.<ref name=\"Library2003\"/><ref name=\"DR\"/>\n\nKircher explained that while Noah had built the Ark, the design came directly from God himself, ensuring that its form was thus a concrete manifestation of divine intelligence. Its dimensions served to rule out another matter which the work discussed: the Book of Genesis records that there were giants on the earth in ancient times, and some held that Noah himself was one of them.  Kircher demonstrated that the size of the Ark made this impossible - there would not have been room for a family of giants on board alongside all the animals. This affirmation of Noah's humanity allowed Kircher to show that the Ark represented not only the human body, vehicle of the living soul, but also symbolised the Church itself, just as Noah prefigured Christ as mediator between God and sinful mankind.<ref name=\"DR\"/>\n\n==Classification of animals in the ark==\n[[File:Arca Noe, arrangement inside ark, by A. Kircher. Wellcome L0013358.jpg|thumb|Internal arrangement of the ark, ''Arca No\u00eb'']]\nKircher sought to account for how different kinds of animal was accommodated in the Ark, and to do this, he classified them, focusing mainly on [[Old World]] species. Echoing [[Pliny]], he ignored the taxonomies of his contemporary scholars and simply classified them by size, from the elephant downwards. He went on to explain how they would have been accommodated, with plant-eaters separated from meat-eaters, land-dwellers from amphibians and water creatures, and 'clean' from 'unclean'.<ref name=\"Zoo\">{{cite book|last1=Enenkel |first1=Karl A. (ed.)|last2=Smith |first2=Paul J. (ed.)|title=Zoology in Early Modern Culture: Intersections of Science, Theology, Philology, and Political and Religious Education|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KQoSBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA105|date=13 October 2014|publisher=BRILL|isbn=978-90-04-27917-9|pages=105\u20138}}</ref>\n\nThe chart showing the floor plan for the Ark shows how the animals were housed. On the lower deck one side berthed beavers, otters, crocodiles, hippopotami, goat-stags, gazelles, elks, bison, goats, sheep, cattle, deer, reindeer, wild goats, gazelles, chamois, fallow deer, dogs, aquatic hare-hounds, Molossian hounds, Maltese dogs, Indian dogs, seals, turtles, hedgehogs, porcupines, badgers, dormice, martens and weasels.  The other wise housed small Indian pigs, rabbits, hares, squirrels, monkeys, apes, cats, asses, donkeys, horses, dromedaries, camels, elephants, rhinoceroses, lions, bears, tigers, panthers, leopards, unicorns, other horned animals from Africa, lynxes, gluttons, wolves, foxes, wild boars and domestic pigs.<ref name=\"Godwin\"/>{{rp|102}}\n\nThe middle deck carried food and supplies both for the voyage and for life after it. On one side were stored agricultural tools, clothes and household linens, metal goods, wool, mills bread ovens and a furnace, oil, salt, assorted materials for use after the Flood, dried fish and fish preserved in salt water, candles, honey, a dovecote, a chicken-coop, acorns, nuts, dried fruit, rice and pulses, casks of water, straw and hay. On the other side were rope and household goods, wood, spices, grains and berries, fruit, bread, smoked meat, a sheep-fold and a goat-fold for feeding the carnivorous animals, butter, cheese, wheat, barley and oats, water, tree-leaves and hay for winter feed, as well as cattle, horses and asses for use after the Flood.<ref name=\"Godwin\"/>{{rp|102}}\n\nThe top deck housed the cabins for Noah and his family, and apart from this was given over to birds.  One one side were river swallows, kingbirds, tits, corncrakes, creepers, shrikes, gryphon-falcons, harpies, doves, pigeons, chickens and fowl, with an aviary for small songbirds, crows, jackdaws and woodpeckers, sparrows, hoopoes, peacocks, cuckoos, robins, swallows quail and birds of paradise.  On the other side were pelicans, spoonbills, pheasants, grouse, partridge, kingfishers, magpies, parrots, peacocks, turkeys, hawks, vultures, eagles, falcons, ostriches, cranes, storks, herons, geese, ducks, kites, coots, fig-peckers, oyster-catchers, starlings, wagtails, owls and bustards.<ref name=\"Godwin\"/>{{rp|102}}\n\n==Animals not carried in the ark==\n[[File:Arca Noe, geography of world after flood, by A. Kircher. Wellcome L0013366.jpg|thumb|Map of the world in ''Arca No\u00eb'' showing how the land area of the world's continents was much larger immediately after the flood]]\nKircher believed - as did many others at his time - that certain animals did not reproduce sexually, but through [[spontaneous generation]].  Such creatures did not need a place in the Ark since they could simply produce themselves from dung or mud. In Kircher's account this included small mammals such as mice and voles, as well as reptiles and insects.<ref name=\"Cole2016\">{{cite book|author=Lucinda Cole|title=Imperfect Creatures: Vermin, Literature, and the Sciences of Life, 1600-1740|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lCalCwAAQBAJ|date=26 February 2016|publisher=University of Michigan Press|isbn=978-0-472-05295-0|page=16}}</ref><ref name=\"MP\"/>{{rp|62}} Kircher did say that snakes were taken on the Ark, partly because of their unique medicinal value, and partly too as food for some of the birds on board.<ref name=\"MP\"/>{{rp|62}} He also excluded from all animals he regarded as 'hybrid', including the giraffe. These creatures he argued were descended from offspring of different animals carried on the ark which later interbred. He considered the [[armadillo]] to be a hybrid of the hedgehog and the turtle, and the [[alpine marmot]] to be a mixture of the badger and the squirrel.<ref name=\"Zoo\"/>\n\nKircher also explained that many of the creatures of the [[New World]] did not need to have a place in the Ark. The original creatures of God's creation came from the [[Garden of Eden]] and were adapted to its climate; as they spread out over the world after the Flood they adapted to different climates and conditions, evolving over time into the new forms seen today.<ref name=\"Zoo\"/> Through these arguments, Kircher was able to show that the Biblical dimensions of the Ark (198 metres long, 33 metres wide and 19,8 metres high) afforded sufficient space to allow the ancestors of all modern creatures in the world to be carried.<ref name=\"MP\"/>{{rp|62}}\n\n==Illustrations==\n[[File:Frontispiece of Athanasius Kircher's \"Arca Noe\" (1675).tif|thumb|Frontispiece of Athanasius Kircher's \"Arca No\u00eb\" (1675)]]\n''Arca No\u00eb'' was dedicated to the twelve year-old king [[Charles II of Spain]]. Its attractiveness to children has been remarked on, with its lavish illustrations and half-playful tone.<ref name=\"Library2003\"/> The dedication compared Noah's Ark to Charles' empire, pointing out that \"what Noah had in a small space, you, High King, possess scattered throughout your realm.\"<ref name=\"Godwin\"/>{{rp|17}} \n''Arca No\u00eb'' included many illustrations, detailing the design and construction of the ark and the animals preserved in it.<ref name=\"Rudwick1995\">{{cite book|author=Martin J. S. Rudwick|title=Scenes from Deep Time: Early Pictorial Representations of the Prehistoric World|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=G-eEDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA256|date=8 November 1995|publisher=University of Chicago Press|isbn=978-0-226-14903-5|page=256}}</ref>  \n\nThe frontispiece depicted God directing [[putti]] bearing a flaming sword, [[alpha and omega]], above the dove the [[Holy Spirit]].  Beneath them, surrounded by lost souls struggling in the waves to reach it, the Ark is afloat on the Flood, representing the Church with Christ keeping watch in the [[crow's nest]] and the words \"Extra quam non est salus\" (\"outside of which there is no salvation\") on its sail. The foreground shows Noah and his family giving thanks for their salvation.<ref name=\"Godwin\"/>{{rp|42}} \n\nThe interior of the book contained over 100 woodcut illustrations, including maps, charts and folding diagrams.  Three of he finest illustrations were by [[Coenraet Decker]] - the portrait of Charles II, Noah and His Progeny, and the Submerged Mountains. ''Arca No\u00eb'' also contains the largest illustration contained in any of Kircher\u2019s books. This was the cutaway diagram of the interior of the Ark, showing where the animals were housed. Measuring 39 x 17 \u00bd inches, it was made from three separate plates and folded out of the book. An entire section of the work was devoted to animals Kircher considered to be hybrid. As well as allowing Kircher to minimise the number of animals requiring space on the Ark, these hybrids also provided a good opportunity for including many exotic and fanciful illustrations to attract the interest of the book's young patron.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Spindler |first1=Christine |title=A Flood of Faith and Knowledge: Kircher\u2019s Arca N\u00f6e |url=https://johnjburnslibrary.wordpress.com/2013/05/06/kircherarcanoe/ |website=johnjburnslibrary.wordpress.com |publisher=John J Burns Library |accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==External links==\n*[https://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k111864r.texteImage digital copy of Arca No\u00eb]\n\n==Bibliography==\n* Don Cameron Allen, ''The Arca Noe of Athanasius Kircher'' in ''The Legend of Noah: Renaissance Rationalism in Art, Science and Letters'', Urbana 1949\n* Davis A. Young, ''The Biblical Flood: A Case Study of the Church's Response to Extrabiblical Evidence'', Eerdmans 1995\n\n==References==\n{{commons category|Arca Noe, by Athanasius Kircher}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Obsolete scientific theories]]\n[[Category:Historicity of the Bible]]\n[[Category:1675 in science]]\n[[Category:1675 works]]\n", "text_old": "\n\n[[File:Arca Noe, why ark did not sink, by A. Kircher. Wellcome L0013361.jpg|thumb|Explanation of why Noah's Ark did not sink, despite its size, from ''Arca No\u00eb'']]\n[[File:Arca Noe, building the ark, by A. Kircher. Wellcome L0013357.jpg|thumb|Building the ark, in ''Arca No\u00eb'']]\n[[File:Houghton GC6 K6323 675a (A) - Optica projectio.jpg |thumb|Cutaway view of Noah's Ark, illustration from ''Arca No\u00eb''|alt=Internal view of Noah's Ark Wellcome L0032185.jpg]]\n\n'''''Arca No\u00eb''''' (\u201cNoah\u2019s Ark\u201d) was a book published in 1675 by the [[Jesuit]] scholar [[Athanasius Kircher]]. It was a study of the biblical story of [[Noah\u2019s Ark]], published by the cartographer and bookseller Johannes van Waesbergen in Amsterdam.<ref name=\"Young2007\">{{cite book|author=David Young|title=The Discovery of Evolution|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vlAJwmWWF80C&pg=PA263|date=9 August 2007|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-86803-7|page=263}}</ref><ref name=\"Library2003\">{{cite book|author=Harold B. Lee Library|title=Athanasius Kircher (1602-1680), Jesuit Scholar: An Exhibition of His Works in the Harold B. Lee Library Collections at Brigham Young University|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=29984eQF86UC&pg=PA65|year=2003|publisher=Martino Publishing|isbn=978-1-57898-432-9|page=65}}</ref> Kircher's aim in ''Arca No\u00eb'' was to reconcile recent discoveries in nature and geography with the text of the Bible. This demonstration of the underlying unity and truth between revelation and science was a fundamental task of Catholic scholarship at the time.<ref name=\"DR\"/> Together with its sister volume ''Turris Babel'' (\u201c[[The Tower of Babel]]\u201d), ''Arca No\u00eb'' presented a complete intellectual project to demonstrate how contemporary science supported the account of the [[Book of Genesis]].<ref name=\"MP\"/>{{rp|61}}<ref name=\"Godwin\">{{cite book |last1=Godwin |first1=Joscelyn |title=Athanasius Kircher's Theatre of the World |date=2015 |publisher=Inner Traditions |location=Rochester, Vermont |isbn=978-1-62055-465-4}}</ref>{{rp|21}}\n\n==Structure==\nThe work was divided into three volumes: the first, ''De rebus quae ante Diluvium'', dealt with the story of Noah before the Flood, the building of the Ark, the choice of animals to go on board and how they were accommodated. The second, ''De iis, quae ipso Diluvio e jusque duratione'', concerned the Flood itself and how the Ark was managed while the flood lasted, as well as providing a mystical and allegorical explanation of its meaning, as a vessel carrying the human soul. The third volume, ''De iis, quae post Diluvium \u00e0 No\u00ebmo gesta sunt'', discussed the deeds of Noah after the Flood, compared the lands of the world as they had been before it and after, and explained how both people and animals dispersed over the globe.<ref name=\"DR\">{{cite web |last1=Dias Klautau |first1=Fabiana |last2=Roxo Beltran |first2=Maria Helena |title=Ci\u00eancia e T\u00e9cnica no livro do G\u00eaneses: a constru\u00e7\u00e3o da Arca de No\u00e9 na percep\u00e7\u00e3o do padre jesu\u00edta Athanasius Kircher (1602-1680) |url=https://www.16snhct.sbhc.org.br/resources/anais/8/1545141369_ARQUIVO_TextocompletoKlautau_Beltran_SBHC2018(rev).pdf |website=16snhct.sbhc.org.b |publisher=Semin\u00e1rio Nacional de Hist\u00f3ria da Ci\u00eancia e da Tecnologia |accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Ideas discussed==\nBy the middle of the seventeenth century, the abundance and diversity of life discovered in the [[New World]] was calling into question the previously unchallenged belief that all life on earth originated from a single point of dispersal - [[Mount Ararat]], after [[Genesis flood narrative|the Flood]]. One of the uncertainties which Kircher addressed in ''Arca No\u00eb'' was how animals had managed to colonise lands so distant across the seas. Another, to which he devoted particular attention, was how so many creatures could have fitted into the Ark at all.<ref name=\"MP\">{{cite journal |last1=Moraes dos Santos |first1=Christian Fausto |last2=Pereira Neto |first2=Juscelino |title=A natureza americana nas obras Turris Babel e Arca N\u00f6e do jesu\u00edta Athanasius Kircher|journal=Revista Brasileira de Hist\u00f3ria das Religi\u00f5es |date=May 2011 |volume=4 |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/236991808_A_natureza_americana_nas_obras_Turris_Babel_e_Arca_Noe_do_jesuita_Athanasius_Kircher_-_The_american_nature_in_the_jesuit_Athanasius_Kirchers_opuses_Turris_Babel_and_Arca_Noe/citation/download |accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref>{{rp|55-56}}                                                       \n\nKircher had first discussed the question of the size of the Ark in 1640 during a mathematical convention to celebrate the centenary of the Jesuit order. Here he delivered a technical paper on Noah's Ark, discussing the exact length of a Biblical [[cubit]].<ref name=\"Temple2006\">{{cite book|author=Nicholas Temple|title=Disclosing Horizons: Architecture, Perspective and Redemptive Space|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=deeQwGAk3aQC&pg=PA167|date=22 November 2006|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-134-11708-6|page=167}}</ref>\nIn ''Arca No\u00eb'', taking the dimensions given in the Bible, Kircher explained how it was possible that all the animals in the contemporary world could originate from a vessel of such limited size.<ref>{{cite web |title=L'Arca Noe di Athanasius Kircher (1675) |url=https://sbs.uniroma1.it/mostra/conoscenzaemisericordia/it/70/larca-noe-di-athanasius-kircher-1675 |website=sbs.uniroma1.it |publisher=Sapienza Universit\u00e0 di Roma |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> The Book of Genesis does not identify the animals taken into the Ark, describing them only as both \u201cclean\u201d and \u201cunclean\u201d. Kircher therefore speculated about which animals were aboard, how they were accommodated, and used this as a basis for working out how it could have been designed and constructed.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Phillips |first1=Amy E. |title=The Fantastic Beasts of Athanasius Kircher |url=https://www.library.georgetown.edu/woodstock/blog/fantastic-beasts-athanasius-kircher |website=library.georgetown.edu |publisher=Georgetown University |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> He also described details such as the exact year of the Flood (2396 BC), the time between the fall of the fist raindrop and Noah setting foot on dry land (365 days), where the Ark landed, and how the creatures spread over the earth after the Flood abated.<ref name=\"Library2003\"/><ref name=\"DR\"/>\n\nKircher explained that while Noah had built the Ark, the design came directly from God himself, ensuring that its form was thus a concrete manifestation of divine intelligence. Its dimensions served to rule out another matter which the work discussed: the Book of Genesis records that there were giants on the earth in ancient times, and some held that Noah himself was one of them.  Kircher demonstrated that the size of the Ark made this impossible - there would not have been room for a family of giants on board alongside all the animals. This affirmation of Noah's humanity allowed Kircher to show that the Ark represented not only the human body, vehicle of the living soul, but also symbolised the Church itself, just as Noah prefigured Christ as mediator between God and sinful mankind.<ref name=\"DR\"/>\n\n==Classification of animals in the ark==\n[[File:Arca Noe, arrangement inside ark, by A. Kircher. Wellcome L0013358.jpg|thumb|Internal arrangement of the ark, ''Arca No\u00eb'']]\nKircher sought to account for how different kinds of animal was accommodated in the Ark, and to do this, he classified them, focusing mainly on [[Old World]] species. Echoing [[Pliny]], he ignored the taxonomies of his contemporary scholars and simply classified them by size, from the elephant downwards. He went on to explain how they would have been accommodated, with plant-eaters separated from meat-eaters, land-dwellers from amphibians and water creatures, and 'clean' from 'unclean'.<ref name=\"Zoo\">{{cite book|last1=Enenkel |first1=Karl A. (ed.)|last2=Smith |first2=Paul J. (ed.)|title=Zoology in Early Modern Culture: Intersections of Science, Theology, Philology, and Political and Religious Education|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KQoSBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA105|date=13 October 2014|publisher=BRILL|isbn=978-90-04-27917-9|pages=105\u20138}}</ref>\n\nThe chart showing the floor plan for the Ark shows how the animals were housed. On the lower deck one side berthed beavers, otters, crocodiles, hippopotami, goat-stags, gazelles, elks, bison, goats, sheep, cattle, deer, reindeer, wild goats, gazelles, chamois, fallow deer, dogs, aquatic hare-hounds, Molossian hounds, Maltese dogs, Indian dogs, seals, turtles, hedgehogs, porcupines, badgers, dormice, martens and weasels.  The other wise housed small Indian pigs, rabbits, hares, squirrels, monkeys, apes, cats, asses, donkeys, horses, dromedaries, camels, elephants, rhinoceroses, lions, bears, tigers, panthers, leopards, unicorns, other horned animals from Africa, lynxes, gluttons, wolves, foxes, wild boars and domestic pigs.<ref name=\"Godwin\"/>{{rp|102}}\n\nThe middle deck carried food and supplies both for the voyage and for life after it. On one side were stored agricultural tools, clothes and household linens, metal goods, wool, mills bread ovens and a furnace, oil, salt, assorted materials for use after the Flood, dried fish and fish preserved in salt water, candles, honey, a dovecote, a chicken-coop, acorns, nuts, dried fruit, rice and pulses, casks of water, straw and hay. On the other side were rope and household goods, wood, spices, grains and berries, fruit, bread, smoked meat, a sheep-fold and a goat-fold for feeding the carnivorous animals, butter, cheese, wheat, barley and oats, water, tree-leaves and hay for winter feed, as well as cattle, horses and asses for use after the Flood.<ref name=\"Godwin\"/>{{rp|102}}\n\nThe top deck housed the cabins for Noah and his family, and apart from this was given over to birds.  One one side were river swallows, kingbirds, tits, corncrakes, creepers, shrikes, gryphon-falcons, harpies, doves, pigeons, chickens and fowl, with an aviary for small songbirds, crows, jackdaws and woodpeckers, sparrows, hoopoes, peacocks, cuckoos, robins, swallows quail and birds of paradise.  On the other side were pelicans, spoonbills, pheasants, grouse, partridge, kingfishers, magpies, parrots, peacocks, turkeys, hawks, vultures, eagles, falcons, ostriches, cranes, storks, herons, geese, ducks, kites, coots, fig-peckers, oyster-catchers, starlings, wagtails, owls and bustards.<ref name=\"Godwin\"/>{{rp|102}}\n\n==Animals not carried in the ark==\n[[File:Arca Noe, geography of world after flood, by A. Kircher. Wellcome L0013366.jpg|thumb|Map of the world in ''Arca No\u00eb'' showing how the land area of the world's continents was much larger immediately after the flood]]\nKircher believed - as did many others at his time - that certain animals did not reproduce sexually, but through [[spontaneous generation]].  Such creatures did not need a place in the Ark since they could simply produce themselves from dung or mud. In Kircher's account this included small mammals such as mice and voles, as well as reptiles and insects.<ref name=\"Cole2016\">{{cite book|author=Lucinda Cole|title=Imperfect Creatures: Vermin, Literature, and the Sciences of Life, 1600-1740|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lCalCwAAQBAJ|date=26 February 2016|publisher=University of Michigan Press|isbn=978-0-472-05295-0|page=16}}</ref><ref name=\"MP\"/>{{rp|62}} Kircher did say that snakes were taken on the Ark, partly because of their unique medicinal value, and partly too as food for some of the birds on board.<ref name=\"MP\"/>{{rp|62}} He also excluded from all animals he regarded as 'hybrid', including the giraffe. These creatures he argued were descended from offspring of different animals carried on the ark which later interbred. He considered the [[armadillo]] to be a hybrid of the hedgehog and the turtle, and the [[alpine marmot]] to be a mixture of the badger and the squirrel.<ref name=\"Zoo\"/>\n\nKircher also explained that many of the creatures of the [[New World]] did not need to have a place in the Ark. The original creatures of God's creation came from the [[Garden of Eden]] and were adapted to its climate; as they spread out over the world after the Flood they adapted to different climates and conditions, evolving over time into the new forms seen today.<ref name=\"Zoo\"/> Through these arguments, Kircher was able to show that the Biblical dimensions of the Ark (198 metres long, 33 metres wide and 19,8 metres high) afforded sufficient space to allow the ancestors of all modern creatures in the world to be carried.<ref name=\"MP\"/>{{rp|62}}\n\n==Illustrations==\n[[File:Frontispiece of Athanasius Kircher's \"Arca Noe\" (1675).tif|thumb|Frontispiece of Athanasius Kircher's \"Arca No\u00eb\" (1675)]]\n''Arca No\u00eb'' was dedicated to the twelve year-old king [[Charles II of Spain]]. Its attractiveness to children has been remarked on, with its lavish illustrations and half-playful tone.<ref name=\"Library2003\"/> The dedication compared Noah's Ark to Charles' empire, pointing out that \"what Noah had in a small space, you, High King, possess scattered throughout your realm.\"<ref name=\"Godwin\"/>{{rp|17}} \n''Arca No\u00eb'' included many illustrations, detailing the design and construction of the ark and the animals preserved in it.<ref name=\"Rudwick1995\">{{cite book|author=Martin J. S. Rudwick|title=Scenes from Deep Time: Early Pictorial Representations of the Prehistoric World|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=G-eEDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA256|date=8 November 1995|publisher=University of Chicago Press|isbn=978-0-226-14903-5|page=256}}</ref>  \n\nThe frontispiece depicted God directing [[putti]] bearing a flaming sword, [[alpha and omega]], above the dove the [[Holy Spirit]].  Beneath them, surrounded by lost souls struggling in the waves to reach it, the Ark is afloat on the Flood, representing the Church with Christ keeping watch in the [[crow's nest]] and the words \"Extra quam non est salus\" (\"outside of which there is no salvation\") on its sail. The foreground shows Noah and his family giving thanks for their salvation.<ref name=\"Godwin\"/>{{rp|42}} \n\nThe interior of the book contained over 100 woodcut illustrations, including maps, charts and folding diagrams.  Three of he finest illustrations were by [[Coenraet Decker]] - the portrait of Charles II, Noah and His Progeny, and the Submerged Mountains. ''Arca No\u00eb'' also contains the largest illustration contained in any of Kircher\u2019s books. This was the cutaway diagram of the interior of the Ark, showing where the animals were housed. Measuring 39 x 17 \u00bd inches, it was made from three separate plates and folded out of the book. An entire section of the work was devoted to animals Kircher considered to be hybrid. As well as allowing Kircher to minimise the number of animals requiring space on the Ark, these hybrids also provided a good opportunity for including many exotic and fanciful illustrations to attract the interest of the book's young patron.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Spindler |first1=Christine |title=A Flood of Faith and Knowledge: Kircher\u2019s Arca N\u00f6e |url=https://johnjburnslibrary.wordpress.com/2013/05/06/kircherarcanoe/ |website=johnjburnslibrary.wordpress.com |publisher=John J Burns Library |accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==External links==\n*[https://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k111864r.texteImage digital copy of Arca No\u00eb]\n\n==Bibliography==\n* Don Cameron Allen, ''The Arca Noe of Athanasius Kircher'' in ''The Legend of Noah: Renaissance Rationalism in Art, Science and Letters'', Urbana 1949\n* Davis A. Young, ''The Biblical Flood: A Case Study of the Church's Response to Extrabiblical Evidence'', Eerdmans 1995\n\n==References==\n{{commons category|Arca Noe, by Athanasius Kircher}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Obsolete scientific theories]]\n[[Category:Historicity of the Bible]]\n[[Category:1675 in science]]\n[[Category:1675 works]]\n", "name_user": "Mccapra", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arca_No%C3%AB"}
{"title_page": "Breast imaging", "text_new": "{{for|non-medical images of breasts|Depictions of nudity}}\n[[File:Breast imaging using pet (1).jpg|thumb|[[Positron emission mammography]] is one of several methods of breast imaging.]]\n\nIn medicine, '''breast imaging''' is the representation or reproduction of a breast's form. There are various methods of breast imaging.\n\n==X-ray==\n\n===Mammography===\n{{main|Mammography}}\n\n[[File:Diagnosis - Mammography.jpg|thumb|The best mammographic images are produced when the breast is compressed.]]\n\nMammography is the process of using low-energy [[X-ray]]s (usually around 30 [[Peak kilovoltage|kVp]]) to examine the human [[breast]], which is used as a diagnostic and screening tool. The goal of mammography is the early detection of [[breast cancer]], typically through detection of characteristic masses and/or [[microcalcification]]s. For the average woman, the [[United States Preventive Services Task Force|U.S. Preventive Services Task Force]] recommended (2009) mammography every two years in women between the ages of 50 and 74.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.uspreventiveservicestaskforce.org/Page/Topic/recommendation-summary/breast-cancer-screening |title=Breast Cancer: Screening |work=United States Preventive Services Task Force |accessdate=}}</ref> The American College of Radiology and American Cancer Society recommend yearly screening mammography starting at age 40.<ref>{{cite web|title=Breast Cancer Early Detection|url=http://www.cancer.org/cancer/breastcancer/moreinformation/breastcancerearlydetection/breast-cancer-early-detection-acs-recs|website=cancer.org|accessdate=29 July 2014|date=2013-09-17}}</ref> The Canadian Task Force on Preventive Health Care (2012) and the European Cancer Observatory (2011) recommends mammography every 2\u20133 years between 50 and 69.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cmaj.ca/content/183/17/1991.full |title=Recommendations on screening for breast cancer in average-risk women aged 40\u201374 years |accessdate=2013-02-21 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://eu-cancer.iarc.fr/cancer-13-breast-screening.html,en |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2015-09-21 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120211011840/http://eu-cancer.iarc.fr/cancer-13-breast-screening.html%2Cen |archivedate=2012-02-11 }}</ref> These task force reports point out that in addition to unnecessary surgery and anxiety, the risks of more frequent mammograms include a small but significant increase in breast cancer induced by radiation.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ahrq.gov/clinic/3rduspstf/breastCancer/brcanrr.htm#ref31 |title=Breast Cancer: Screening |work=United States Preventive Services Task Force |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130616040709/http://www.ahrq.gov/clinic/3rduspstf/breastcancer/brcanrr.htm#ref31 |archivedate=2013-06-16 }}</ref><ref name=Friedenson00>{{cite journal | author = Friedenson B | title = Is mammography indicated for women with defective BRCA genes? Implications of recent scientific advances for the diagnosis, treatment, and prevention of hereditary breast cancer | journal = MedGenMed | volume = 2 | issue = 1 | pages = E9 |date= March 2000 | pmid = 11104455 | doi =  | url = http://www.medscape.com/Medscape/GeneralMedicine/journal/2000/v02.n02/mgm0309.frie/mgm0309.frie-01.html }}</ref> Additionally, mammograms should not be done with any increased frequency in people undergoing breast surgery, including breast enlargement, mastopexy, and breast reducation.<ref>{{Citation|author1=American Society of Plastic Surgeons |author1-link=American Society of Plastic Surgeons |date=24 April 2014 |title=Five Things Physicians and Patients Should Question |publisher=American Society of Plastic Surgeons |work=[[Choosing Wisely]]: an initiative of the [[ABIM Foundation]] |url=http://www.choosingwisely.org/doctor-patient-lists/american-society-of-plastic-surgeons/ |accessdate=25 July 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140719103909/http://www.choosingwisely.org/doctor-patient-lists/american-society-of-plastic-surgeons/ |archivedate=19 July 2014 }}</ref> The [[Cochrane Collaboration]] (2013) concluded that the trials with adequate randomisation did not find an effect of mammography screening on total cancer mortality, including breast cancer, after 10 years. The authors of systematic review write: \"If we assume that screening reduces breast cancer mortality by 15% and that overdiagnosis and overtreatment is at 30%, it means that for every 2000 women invited for screening throughout 10 years, one will avoid dying of breast cancer and 10 healthy women, who would not have been diagnosed if there had not been screening, will be treated unnecessarily. Furthermore, more than 200 women will experience important psychological distress including anxiety and uncertainty for years because of false positive findings.\"  The authors conclude that the time has come to re-assess whether universal mammography screening should be recommended for any age group.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=G\u00f8tzsche PC, J\u00f8rgensen KJ | title = Screening for breast cancer with mammography | journal = Cochrane Database Syst Rev | volume =  6| issue = 6 | pages = CD001877 | year = 2013 | pmid = 23737396 | doi = 10.1002/14651858.CD001877.pub5 | pmc=6464778}}</ref> They thus state that universal screening may not be reasonable.{{Citation needed|date=November 2018}} The Nordic Cochrane Collection, which in 2012 reviews updated research to state that advances in diagnosis and treatment make mammography screening less effective today.  They state screening is \u201cno longer effective.\u201d  They conclude that \u201cit therefore no longer seems reasonable to attend\u201d for breast cancer screening at any age, and warn of misleading information on the internet.{{Citation needed|date=November 2018}}\n\nMammography has a false-negative (missed cancer) rate of between 7 and 12 percent.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ww5.komen.org/BreastCancer/AccuracyofMammograms.html|title=Mammogram Accuracy - Accuracy of Mammograms|website=ww5.komen.org|access-date=2018-11-07}}</ref> This is partly due to [[optical density|dense]] tissues obscuring the cancer and the fact that the appearance of cancer on mammograms has a large overlap with the appearance of normal tissues.  A meta-analysis review of programs in countries with organized screening found 52% over-diagnosis.{{Citation needed|date=November 2018}}Digital breast tomosynthesis\n\nDigital breast [[tomosynthesis]] (DBT) can provide a higher diagnostic accuracy compared to conventional mammography.  In DBT, like conventional mammography, compression is used to improve image quality and decreases radiation dose.  The laminographic imaging technique dates back to the 1930s and belongs to the category of geometric or linear tomography.<ref>Dedicated Computed Tomography of the Breast: Image Processing and Its Impact on Breast Mass Detectability. Qing Xia. 2007. {{ISBN|0549663193}} pp.4</ref>\n\nBecause the data acquired are very high resolution (85 \u2013 160 micron typical ), much higher than CT, DBT is unable to offer the  narrow slice widths that CT offers (typically 1-1.5&nbsp;mm). However, the higher resolution detectors permit very high in-plane resolution, even if the Z-axis resolution is less. The primary interest in DBT is in breast imaging, as an extension to [[mammography]], where it offers better detection rates with little extra increase in radiation.<ref>Smith AP, Niklason L, Ren B, Wu T, Ruth C, Jing Z. Lesion Visibility in Low Dose Tomosynthesis. In: Digital mammography : 8th international workshop, IWDM 2006, Manchester, UK, June 18\u201321, 2006 : proceedings. Astley, S, Brady, M, Rose, C, Zwiggelaar, R (Eds.) (Springer, New York, 2006) pp.160.</ref><ref name=\"L\u00e5ngAndersson2014\">{{cite journal |last1=L\u00e5ng| first1=K |last2=Andersson |first2=I |last3=Zackrisson |first3=S |title=Breast cancer detection in digital breast tomosynthesis and digital mammography\u2014a side-by-side review of discrepant cases |journal=The British Journal of Radiology |volume=87 |issue=1040 |year=2014 |pages=20140080 |issn=0007-1285 |doi=10.1259/bjr.20140080 |pmid=24896197 |pmc=4112403}}</ref>\n\nTomosynthesis is now [[Food and Drug Administration]] (FDA) approved for use in [[breast cancer screening]].<ref>\"[https://www.fda.gov/MedicalDevices/ProductsandMedicalProcedures/DeviceApprovalsandClearances/Recently-ApprovedDevices/ucm246400.htm Selenia Dimensions 3D System \u2013 P080003], US Food and Drug Administration (FDA), February 11, 2011</ref>\n\n===Xeromammography===\n{{main|Xeromammography}}\nXeromammography is a [[photoelectric]] method of recording an [[x-ray]] image on a coated metal plate, using low-energy [[photon]] beams, long exposure time, and dry chemical developers. It is a form of [[xeroradiography]].<ref>{{MeshName|Xeromammography}}</ref>\n\nRadiation exposure is an important factor in risk assessment since it makes up 98% of the effective dose. Currently, the mean value of the absorbed dose in the glandular tissue is used as a description of radiation risk since the glandular tissue is the most vulnerable part of the breast.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=S\u00e4bel|first=M.|last2=Aichinger|first2=U.|last3=Schulz-Wendtland|first3=R.|date=2001-02|title=[Radiation exposure in x-ray mammography]|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/11253092|journal=RoFo: Fortschritte Auf Dem Gebiete Der Rontgenstrahlen Und Der Nuklearmedizin|volume=173|issue=2|pages=79\u201391|doi=10.1055/s-2001-10888|issn=1438-9029|pmid=11253092}}</ref>\n\n===Galactography===\n{{main|Galactography}}\nGalactography is a medical diagnostic procedure for viewing the [[milk ducts]]. It is considered a useful procedure in the early diagnosis of patients with pathologic nipple discharge.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bern\u00e1-Serna|first=Juan D.|last2=Torres-Ales|first2=Carolina|last3=Bern\u00e1-Mestre|first3=Juan D.|last4=Polo|first4=Luis|date=May 2013|title=Role of galactography in the early diagnosis of breast cancer|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/24419050|journal=Breast Care (Basel, Switzerland)|volume=8|issue=2|pages=122\u2013126|doi=10.1159/000350779|issn=1661-3791|pmc=3683945|pmid=24419050}}</ref> The standard treatment of galactographically suspicious breast lesions is to perform a surgical intervention on the concerned duct or ducts: if the discharge clearly stems from a single duct, then the excision of the duct ([[microdochectomy]]) is indicated;<ref name=\"RawlinsonAlderson2010-p219\">{{cite book|author1=Nigel Rawlinson|author2=Derek Alderson|title=Surgery: Diagnosis and Management|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fxbDsuew0IkC&pg=PA219|date=29 September 2010|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=978-1-4443-9122-0|pages=219}}</ref> if the discharge comes from several ducts or if no specific duct could be determined, then a subareolar resection of the ducts ([[Hadfield's procedure]]) is performed instead.<ref name=\"RawlinsonAlderson2010-p219\"/> To avoid infection, galactography should not be performed when the nipple discharge contains [[pus]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://radiopaedia.org/articles/breast-ductography-1|title=Breast ductography|publisher=radiopaedia.org|accessdate=4 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n==MRI==\n{{main|Breast MRI}}\n\n[[File:Mri of breast.jpg|thumb|A color-enhanced MRI of a breast]]\n\nBreast MRI, an alternative to mammography, has shown substantial progress in the detection of breast cancer. The available literature suggests that the [[Sensitivity and specificity|sensitivity]] of contrast-enhanced breast MRI in detection of cancer is considerably higher than that of either radiographic mammography or [[ultrasound]] and is generally reported to be in excess of 94%.<ref name=Goscin2001>[http://www.medscape.com/viewarticle/409021_9 Magnetic Resonance Imaging of the Breast]</ref>\n\nThe ''[[Sensitivity and specificity|specificity]]'' (the confidence that a lesion is cancerous and not a [[false positive]]) is only fair ('modest'),<ref name=\"pmid18342764\">{{cite journal |vauthors=DeMartini W, Lehman C, Partridge S |title=Breast MRI for cancer detection and characterization: a review of evidence-based clinical applications |journal=Acad Radiol |volume=15 |issue=4 |pages=408\u201316 |date=April 2008 |pmid=18342764 |doi=10.1016/j.acra.2007.11.006 }}</ref> (or 37%-97%<ref name=Goscin2001/>) thus a ''positive'' finding by MRI should not be interpreted as a definitive diagnosis.\n\nThe reports of 4,271 breast MRIs from eight large scale clinical trials were reviewed in 2006.<ref>{{cite journal | author=Lehman CD | title=Role of MRI in screening women at high risk for breast cancer | journal=Journal of Magnetic Resonance Imaging | volume=24 | issue=5 | year=2006  | pages=964\u201370 | pmid=17036340 | doi=10.1002/jmri.20752}}</ref>\n\nCurrently, American and European guidelines both recommend MRI screening as the optimum imaging modality but differences exist in regards to screening for certain patient subgroups. Specifically, the advantage of MRI screening is increased detection of small cancers which have less associated lymph node involvement and consequently decreased frequency of interval cancers which affect survival and mortality.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Roca|first=S. Alonso|date=31 March 2020|title=Screening in Patients with Increased Risk of Breast Cancer. Pros and Cons of MRI Screening.|url=https://www.elsevier.es/es-revista-radiologia-119-avance-resumen-cribado-pacientes-con-riesgo-incrementado-S0033833820300308#tbl0020|journal=Radiologia|volume=62|pages=237\u2013249|via=Elsevier}}</ref>\n\n==Ultrasound==\n{{main|Breast ultrasound}}\n\n[[File:Ultrasound Scan ND 115254 1159140 cr.png|thumb|Breast ultrasounds may be used with or without a mammogram.]]\n\nBreast ultrasound is the use of [[medical ultrasonography]] to perform imaging of the [[breast]]. It can be considered either a [[diagnostic procedure|diagnostic]] or a [[screening (medicine)|screening]] procedure.<ref name=\"StavrosRapp2004\">{{cite book|author1=A. Thomas Stavros|author2=Cynthia L. Rapp|author3=Steve H. Parker|title=Breast ultrasound|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UkGtw5VI15sC|accessdate=22 August 2010|date=1 January 2004|publisher=Lippincott Williams & Wilkins|isbn=978-0-397-51624-7}}</ref> It may be used either with or without a mammogram.<ref name=\"urlBreast ultrasound: MedlinePlus Medical Encyclopedia\">{{cite web |url=https://www.nlm.nih.gov/medlineplus/ency/article/003379.htm |title=Breast ultrasound: MedlinePlus Medical Encyclopedia |website= |accessdate=2010-08-22}}</ref>\n\n==Scintimammography==\n{{main|Scintimammography}}\nScintimammography is a type of [[breast]] imaging test that is used to detect [[cancer cells]] in the breasts of some women who have had abnormal [[mammogram]]s, or for those who have dense [[breast tissue]], [[breast surgery|post-operative]] scar tissue or [[breast implant]]s, but is not used for [[Breast cancer screening|screening]] or in place of a mammogram. Rather, it is used when the detection of breast abnormalities is not possible or not reliable on the basis of mammography and [[breast ultrasound|ultrasound]]. In the scintimammography procedure, a [[woman]] receives an [[Injection (medicine)|injection]] of a small amount of a [[radioactive]] substance called [[technetium]] 99 [[sestamibi]]. This substance is preferably taken up by cancerous tissues, making them show brightly on the images.<ref name=\"NassHenderson2001\">{{cite book|last1=Nass|first1=Sharyl J.|last2=Henderson|first2=I. Craig|last3=Cancer|first3=Institute of Medicine (U.S.). Committee on Technologies for the Early Detection of Breast|title=Mammography and beyond: developing technologies for the early detection of breast cancer|url=https://archive.org/details/mammographybeyon00comm_0|url-access=registration|accessdate=17 July 2011|year=2001|publisher=National Academies Press|isbn=978-0-309-07283-0|pages=[https://archive.org/details/mammographybeyon00comm_0/page/n131 106]\u2013}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n{{Breast procedures}}\n\n[[Category:Breast imaging|*]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|non-medical images of breasts|Depictions of nudity}}\n[[File:Breast imaging using pet (1).jpg|thumb|[[Positron emission mammography]] is one of several methods of breast imaging.]]\n\nIn medicine, '''breast imaging''' is the representation or reproduction of a breast's form. There are various methods of breast imaging.\n\n==X-ray==\n\n===Mammography===\n{{main|Mammography}}\n\n[[File:Diagnosis - Mammography.jpg|thumb|The best mammographic images are produced when the breast is compressed.]]\n\nMammography is the process of using low-energy [[X-ray]]s (usually around 30 [[Peak kilovoltage|kVp]]) to examine the human [[breast]], which is used as a diagnostic and screening tool. The goal of mammography is the early detection of [[breast cancer]], typically through detection of characteristic masses and/or [[microcalcification]]s. For the average woman, the [[United States Preventive Services Task Force|U.S. Preventive Services Task Force]] recommended (2009) mammography every two years in women between the ages of 50 and 74.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.uspreventiveservicestaskforce.org/Page/Topic/recommendation-summary/breast-cancer-screening |title=Breast Cancer: Screening |work=United States Preventive Services Task Force |accessdate=}}</ref> The American College of Radiology and American Cancer Society recommend yearly screening mammography starting at age 40.<ref>{{cite web|title=Breast Cancer Early Detection|url=http://www.cancer.org/cancer/breastcancer/moreinformation/breastcancerearlydetection/breast-cancer-early-detection-acs-recs|website=cancer.org|accessdate=29 July 2014|date=2013-09-17}}</ref> The Canadian Task Force on Preventive Health Care (2012) and the European Cancer Observatory (2011) recommends mammography every 2\u20133 years between 50 and 69.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cmaj.ca/content/183/17/1991.full |title=Recommendations on screening for breast cancer in average-risk women aged 40\u201374 years |accessdate=2013-02-21 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://eu-cancer.iarc.fr/cancer-13-breast-screening.html,en |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2015-09-21 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120211011840/http://eu-cancer.iarc.fr/cancer-13-breast-screening.html%2Cen |archivedate=2012-02-11 }}</ref> These task force reports point out that in addition to unnecessary surgery and anxiety, the risks of more frequent mammograms include a small but significant increase in breast cancer induced by radiation.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ahrq.gov/clinic/3rduspstf/breastCancer/brcanrr.htm#ref31 |title=Breast Cancer: Screening |work=United States Preventive Services Task Force |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130616040709/http://www.ahrq.gov/clinic/3rduspstf/breastcancer/brcanrr.htm#ref31 |archivedate=2013-06-16 }}</ref><ref name=Friedenson00>{{cite journal | author = Friedenson B | title = Is mammography indicated for women with defective BRCA genes? Implications of recent scientific advances for the diagnosis, treatment, and prevention of hereditary breast cancer | journal = MedGenMed | volume = 2 | issue = 1 | pages = E9 |date= March 2000 | pmid = 11104455 | doi =  | url = http://www.medscape.com/Medscape/GeneralMedicine/journal/2000/v02.n02/mgm0309.frie/mgm0309.frie-01.html }}</ref> Additionally, mammograms should not be done with any increased frequency in people undergoing breast surgery, including breast enlargement, mastopexy, and breast reducation.<ref>{{Citation|author1=American Society of Plastic Surgeons |author1-link=American Society of Plastic Surgeons |date=24 April 2014 |title=Five Things Physicians and Patients Should Question |publisher=American Society of Plastic Surgeons |work=[[Choosing Wisely]]: an initiative of the [[ABIM Foundation]] |url=http://www.choosingwisely.org/doctor-patient-lists/american-society-of-plastic-surgeons/ |accessdate=25 July 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140719103909/http://www.choosingwisely.org/doctor-patient-lists/american-society-of-plastic-surgeons/ |archivedate=19 July 2014 }}</ref> The [[Cochrane Collaboration]] (2013) concluded that the trials with adequate randomisation did not find an effect of mammography screening on total cancer mortality, including breast cancer, after 10 years. The authors of systematic review write: \"If we assume that screening reduces breast cancer mortality by 15% and that overdiagnosis and overtreatment is at 30%, it means that for every 2000 women invited for screening throughout 10 years, one will avoid dying of breast cancer and 10 healthy women, who would not have been diagnosed if there had not been screening, will be treated unnecessarily. Furthermore, more than 200 women will experience important psychological distress including anxiety and uncertainty for years because of false positive findings.\"  The authors conclude that the time has come to re-assess whether universal mammography screening should be recommended for any age group.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=G\u00f8tzsche PC, J\u00f8rgensen KJ | title = Screening for breast cancer with mammography | journal = Cochrane Database Syst Rev | volume =  6| issue = 6 | pages = CD001877 | year = 2013 | pmid = 23737396 | doi = 10.1002/14651858.CD001877.pub5 | pmc=6464778}}</ref> They thus state that universal screening may not be reasonable.{{Citation needed|date=November 2018}} The Nordic Cochrane Collection, which in 2012 reviews updated research to state that advances in diagnosis and treatment make mammography screening less effective today.  They state screening is \u201cno longer effective.\u201d  They conclude that \u201cit therefore no longer seems reasonable to attend\u201d for breast cancer screening at any age, and warn of misleading information on the internet.{{Citation needed|date=November 2018}}\n\nMammography has a false-negative (missed cancer) rate of between 7 and 12 percent.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ww5.komen.org/BreastCancer/AccuracyofMammograms.html|title=Mammogram Accuracy - Accuracy of Mammograms|website=ww5.komen.org|access-date=2018-11-07}}</ref> This is partly due to [[optical density|dense]] tissues obscuring the cancer and the fact that the appearance of cancer on mammograms has a large overlap with the appearance of normal tissues.  A meta-analysis review of programs in countries with organized screening found 52% over-diagnosis.{{Citation needed|date=November 2018}}Digital breast tomosynthesis\n\nDigital breast [[tomosynthesis]] (DBT) can provide a higher diagnostic accuracy compared to conventional mammography.  In DBT, like conventional mammography, compression is used to improve image quality and decreases radiation dose.  The laminographic imaging technique dates back to the 1930s and belongs to the category of geometric or linear tomography.<ref>Dedicated Computed Tomography of the Breast: Image Processing and Its Impact on Breast Mass Detectability. Qing Xia. 2007. {{ISBN|0549663193}} pp.4</ref>\n\nBecause the data acquired are very high resolution (85 \u2013 160 micron typical ), much higher than CT, DBT is unable to offer the  narrow slice widths that CT offers (typically 1-1.5&nbsp;mm). However, the higher resolution detectors permit very high in-plane resolution, even if the Z-axis resolution is less. The primary interest in DBT is in breast imaging, as an extension to [[mammography]], where it offers better detection rates with little extra increase in radiation.<ref>Smith AP, Niklason L, Ren B, Wu T, Ruth C, Jing Z. Lesion Visibility in Low Dose Tomosynthesis. In: Digital mammography : 8th international workshop, IWDM 2006, Manchester, UK, June 18\u201321, 2006 : proceedings. Astley, S, Brady, M, Rose, C, Zwiggelaar, R (Eds.) (Springer, New York, 2006) pp.160.</ref><ref name=\"L\u00e5ngAndersson2014\">{{cite journal |last1=L\u00e5ng| first1=K |last2=Andersson |first2=I |last3=Zackrisson |first3=S |title=Breast cancer detection in digital breast tomosynthesis and digital mammography\u2014a side-by-side review of discrepant cases |journal=The British Journal of Radiology |volume=87 |issue=1040 |year=2014 |pages=20140080 |issn=0007-1285 |doi=10.1259/bjr.20140080 |pmid=24896197 |pmc=4112403}}</ref>\n\nTomosynthesis is now [[Food and Drug Administration]] (FDA) approved for use in [[breast cancer screening]].<ref>\"[https://www.fda.gov/MedicalDevices/ProductsandMedicalProcedures/DeviceApprovalsandClearances/Recently-ApprovedDevices/ucm246400.htm Selenia Dimensions 3D System \u2013 P080003], US Food and Drug Administration (FDA), February 11, 2011</ref>\n\n===Xeromammography===\n{{main|Xeromammography}}\nXeromammography is a [[photoelectric]] method of recording an [[x-ray]] image on a coated metal plate, using low-energy [[photon]] beams, long exposure time, and dry chemical developers. It is a form of [[xeroradiography]].<ref>{{MeshName|Xeromammography}}</ref>\n\nRadiation exposure is an important factor in risk assessment since it makes up 98% of the effective dose. Currently, the mean value of the absorbed dose in the glandular tissue is used as a description of radiation risk since the glandular tissue is the most vulnerable part of the breast.\n\n===Galactography===\n{{main|Galactography}}\nGalactography is a medical diagnostic procedure for viewing the [[milk ducts]]. It is considered a useful procedure in the early diagnosis of patients with pathologic nipple discharge.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bern\u00e1-Serna|first=Juan D.|last2=Torres-Ales|first2=Carolina|last3=Bern\u00e1-Mestre|first3=Juan D.|last4=Polo|first4=Luis|date=May 2013|title=Role of galactography in the early diagnosis of breast cancer|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/24419050|journal=Breast Care (Basel, Switzerland)|volume=8|issue=2|pages=122\u2013126|doi=10.1159/000350779|issn=1661-3791|pmc=3683945|pmid=24419050}}</ref> The standard treatment of galactographically suspicious breast lesions is to perform a surgical intervention on the concerned duct or ducts: if the discharge clearly stems from a single duct, then the excision of the duct ([[microdochectomy]]) is indicated;<ref name=\"RawlinsonAlderson2010-p219\">{{cite book|author1=Nigel Rawlinson|author2=Derek Alderson|title=Surgery: Diagnosis and Management|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fxbDsuew0IkC&pg=PA219|date=29 September 2010|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=978-1-4443-9122-0|pages=219}}</ref> if the discharge comes from several ducts or if no specific duct could be determined, then a subareolar resection of the ducts ([[Hadfield's procedure]]) is performed instead.<ref name=\"RawlinsonAlderson2010-p219\"/> To avoid infection, galactography should not be performed when the nipple discharge contains [[pus]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://radiopaedia.org/articles/breast-ductography-1|title=Breast ductography|publisher=radiopaedia.org|accessdate=4 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n==MRI==\n{{main|Breast MRI}}\n\n[[File:Mri of breast.jpg|thumb|A color-enhanced MRI of a breast]]\n\nBreast MRI, an alternative to mammography, has shown substantial progress in the detection of breast cancer. The available literature suggests that the [[Sensitivity and specificity|sensitivity]] of contrast-enhanced breast MRI in detection of cancer is considerably higher than that of either radiographic mammography or [[ultrasound]] and is generally reported to be in excess of 94%.<ref name=Goscin2001>[http://www.medscape.com/viewarticle/409021_9 Magnetic Resonance Imaging of the Breast]</ref>\n\nThe ''[[Sensitivity and specificity|specificity]]'' (the confidence that a lesion is cancerous and not a [[false positive]]) is only fair ('modest'),<ref name=\"pmid18342764\">{{cite journal |vauthors=DeMartini W, Lehman C, Partridge S |title=Breast MRI for cancer detection and characterization: a review of evidence-based clinical applications |journal=Acad Radiol |volume=15 |issue=4 |pages=408\u201316 |date=April 2008 |pmid=18342764 |doi=10.1016/j.acra.2007.11.006 }}</ref> (or 37%-97%<ref name=Goscin2001/>) thus a ''positive'' finding by MRI should not be interpreted as a definitive diagnosis.\n\nThe reports of 4,271 breast MRIs from eight large scale clinical trials were reviewed in 2006.<ref>{{cite journal | author=Lehman CD | title=Role of MRI in screening women at high risk for breast cancer | journal=Journal of Magnetic Resonance Imaging | volume=24 | issue=5 | year=2006  | pages=964\u201370 | pmid=17036340 | doi=10.1002/jmri.20752}}</ref>\n\nCurrently, American and European guidelines both recommend MRI screening as the optimum imaging modality but differences exist in regards to screening for certain patient subgroups. Specifically, the advantage of MRI screening is increased detection of small cancers which have less associated lymph node involvement and consequently decreased frequency of interval cancers which affect survival and mortality.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Roca|first=S. Alonso|date=31 March 2020|title=Screening in Patients with Increased Risk of Breast Cancer. Pros and Cons of MRI Screening.|url=https://www.elsevier.es/es-revista-radiologia-119-avance-resumen-cribado-pacientes-con-riesgo-incrementado-S0033833820300308#tbl0020|journal=Radiologia|volume=62|pages=237\u2013249|via=Elsevier}}</ref>\n\n==Ultrasound==\n{{main|Breast ultrasound}}\n\n[[File:Ultrasound Scan ND 115254 1159140 cr.png|thumb|Breast ultrasounds may be used with or without a mammogram.]]\n\nBreast ultrasound is the use of [[medical ultrasonography]] to perform imaging of the [[breast]]. It can be considered either a [[diagnostic procedure|diagnostic]] or a [[screening (medicine)|screening]] procedure.<ref name=\"StavrosRapp2004\">{{cite book|author1=A. Thomas Stavros|author2=Cynthia L. Rapp|author3=Steve H. Parker|title=Breast ultrasound|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UkGtw5VI15sC|accessdate=22 August 2010|date=1 January 2004|publisher=Lippincott Williams & Wilkins|isbn=978-0-397-51624-7}}</ref> It may be used either with or without a mammogram.<ref name=\"urlBreast ultrasound: MedlinePlus Medical Encyclopedia\">{{cite web |url=https://www.nlm.nih.gov/medlineplus/ency/article/003379.htm |title=Breast ultrasound: MedlinePlus Medical Encyclopedia |website= |accessdate=2010-08-22}}</ref>\n\n==Scintimammography==\n{{main|Scintimammography}}\nScintimammography is a type of [[breast]] imaging test that is used to detect [[cancer cells]] in the breasts of some women who have had abnormal [[mammogram]]s, or for those who have dense [[breast tissue]], [[breast surgery|post-operative]] scar tissue or [[breast implant]]s, but is not used for [[Breast cancer screening|screening]] or in place of a mammogram. Rather, it is used when the detection of breast abnormalities is not possible or not reliable on the basis of mammography and [[breast ultrasound|ultrasound]]. In the scintimammography procedure, a [[woman]] receives an [[Injection (medicine)|injection]] of a small amount of a [[radioactive]] substance called [[technetium]] 99 [[sestamibi]]. This substance is preferably taken up by cancerous tissues, making them show brightly on the images.<ref name=\"NassHenderson2001\">{{cite book|last1=Nass|first1=Sharyl J.|last2=Henderson|first2=I. Craig|last3=Cancer|first3=Institute of Medicine (U.S.). Committee on Technologies for the Early Detection of Breast|title=Mammography and beyond: developing technologies for the early detection of breast cancer|url=https://archive.org/details/mammographybeyon00comm_0|url-access=registration|accessdate=17 July 2011|year=2001|publisher=National Academies Press|isbn=978-0-309-07283-0|pages=[https://archive.org/details/mammographybeyon00comm_0/page/n131 106]\u2013}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n{{Breast procedures}}\n\n[[Category:Breast imaging|*]]\n", "name_user": "Amircha", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eXeromammography", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Breast_imaging"}
{"title_page": "Steve Green (journalist)", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=October 2011}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2011}}\n[[File:jervaulx 2005.jpg|right|250px|thumb|Ann and Steve Green at [[Jervaulx Abbey]], North Yorkshire, October 2005. Photo by Steve Green.]]\n'''Steve Green''' (born 1960, [[Solihull]], England) is a former newspaper [[reporter]] (1978\u201384) turned freelance journalist, who has also written short fiction and poetry. He is an active member of the science fiction [[science fiction fanzine|press]] and [[science fiction fandom|fan community]].\n\n==Journalism and other writings==\nSubsequent to his career as a newspaper reporter (initially on ''The Walsall Observer'', later on ''The Solihull News''), Green has contributed to such magazines as ''[[The Dark Side (magazine)|The Dark Side]]'' (for which he wrote 51 instalments of the review column \"Fanzine Focus\"), ''[[Interzone (magazine)|Interzone]]'' (interviewing the comics writer and editor [[Stan Lee]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.locusmag.com/index/t469.htm#A24911 |title=''Locus'' index for ''Interzone #59'', May 1992 |publisher=Locusmag.com |accessdate=20 October 2011}}</ref> and the author/screenwriter Peter Atkins<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.locusmag.com/index/t607.htm#A31069 |title=''Locus'' index for ''Interzone #81'', March 1994 |publisher=Locusmag.com |accessdate=20 October 2011}}</ref>), ''Fantasia'' and ''[[SFX (magazine)|SFX]]'', as well as being an occasional contributor to the 1990s [[BBC Radio 5 (former)|BBC Radio 5]] series ''The Way Out''. He wrote an online column on [[real ale]] and the British pub industry for ''[[Sunday Mercury|The Sunday Mercury]]'' in the late 2000s<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.sundaymercury.net/toby-jugg/ |title=Sunday Mercury real ale column |publisher=Blogs.sundaymercury.net |accessdate=20 October 2011}}</ref> and returned to ''The Dark Side'' as a movie reviewer in 2015.\n\nWith [[Martin Tudor (science fiction activist)|Martin Tudor]], he was also the co-editor/publisher of the science fiction journal ''[[Critical Wave]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.minervatech.u-net.com/people01.htm |title=Eulogy for the award-winning British sf author Bob Shaw, originally written by Green for ''Critical Wave'' in 1996 |publisher=Minervatech.u-net.com |accessdate=20 October 2011}}</ref> from its launch in October 1987 to its financial heat-death in mid-1996;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.ansible.co.uk/a111.html |title=''Ansible #111'' (ed. Dave Langford, October 1996): \"Sad news, indeed\" |publisher=News.ansible.co.uk |accessdate=20 October 2011}}</ref> a new, online edition was announced in September 2008,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://efanzines.com/DrinkTank/DrinkTank183.pdf |title=''The Drink Tank #183'' (ed. Chris Garcia, October 2008), announcing relaunch of ''Critical Wave'' |accessdate=20 October 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.ansible.co.uk/a255.html |title=''Ansible #255'' (ed. Dave Langford, October 2008), announcing relaunch of ''Critical Wave'' |publisher=News.ansible.co.uk |accessdate=20 October 2011}}</ref> with the same editorial team; the first issue of this new series was released in November 2008, but a second has yet to appear.\n\nIn addition to having several of his own short stories published, including \"Cracking\" in ''The Anthology of Fantasy & the Supernatural'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.locusmag.com/index/t591.htm#A30402 |title=''Locus'' index for ''The Anthology of Fantasy and the Supernatural'' (ed. Stephen Jones and David Sutton; Tiger Books, 1994) |publisher=Locusmag.com |accessdate=20 October 2011}}</ref> plus a large number of poems,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.locusmag.com/index/t477.htm#A25052 |title=''Locus'' index to ''Works #8'' (1992) |publisher=Locusmag.com |accessdate=20 October 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://fr.bookbutler.com/do/bookSearch;jsessionid=6D108A30E5288AC423214AC97A7CE7E5?pageNr=1&showMore=true&sortBy=salesrank&searchFor=1+85731+439+5&searchBy=isbn&searchIn=uk&shipTo=gb&amountIn=gbp&zip= |title=''That's Entertainment'', edited by Kerrie Pateman (Poetry Now, 1995), ISBN 1-85731-439-5 |publisher=Fr.bookbutler.com |accessdate=20 October 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://fr.bookbutler.com/do/bookSearch?showMore=true&shipTo=gb&amountIn=gbp&zip=&sortBy=salesrank&pageNr=1&searchFor=0907376150&searchBy=isbn&searchIn=uk |title=''Dreamers on the Sea of Fate'', edited by Steve Sneyd (Sol, 1999), ISBN 0-907376-15-0 |publisher=Fr.bookbutler.com |accessdate=20 October 2011}}</ref> Green appears as a supporting character in both [[David Langford]]'s comic novel ''The Leaky Establishment''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ansible.co.uk/books/leaky2.jpg |title=Cover of the 1985 paperback edition of ''The Leaky Establishment''; the character named for Green can be seen emerging from the pub, notebook in hand |accessdate=20 October 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927025101/http://www.ansible.co.uk/books/leaky2.jpg |archive-date=27 September 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and [[Joel Lane]]'s novella ''The Witnesses Are Gone''<ref>[http://store.pspublishing.co.uk/acatalog/info_417.html PS Publishing catalogue entry for ''The Witnesses Are Gone'' by Joel Lane]</ref> (the latter also features his late wife, Ann Green).\n\nDuring the mid-1990s, Green was a regular columnist for both the [[Seattle]] [[freesheet]] ''Mansplat!''<ref>http://www.mansplat.com/ ''Mansplat!'' website, including partial index</ref> and the focal point American [[fanzine]] ''Apparatchik'' (examples:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://efanzines.com/Apparatchik/65-green.html |title=\"Fannish Memory Syndrome\" column in ''Apparatchik #65'', 8 August 1996 |publisher=Efanzines.com |date=8 August 1996 |accessdate=20 October 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://efanzines.com/Apparatchik/66-green.html |title=\"Fannish Memory Syndrome\" column in ''Apparatchik #66'', 29 August 1996 |publisher=Efanzines.com |date=29 August 1996 |accessdate=20 October 2011}}</ref><ref>[http://efanzines.com/Apparatchik/71-green.htm \"Fannish Memory Syndrome]\" column in ''Apparatchik #71'', 13 December 1996]{{dead link|date=October 2011}}</ref>). His ''Apparatchik'' column, \"Fannish Memory Syndrome\", was relaunched in the [[Hugo Award for Best Amateur Magazine|Hugo Award]]-nominated US fanzine ''The Drink Tank''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://efanzines.com/DrinkTank/ |title=Bill Burns' eFanzines index of links to downloadable issues of 'The Drink Tank' |publisher=Efanzines.com |date=7 July 2005 |accessdate=20 October 2011}}</ref> in September 2007.<ref>http://efanzines.com/DrinkTank/DrinkTank143.pdf</ref> Selected examples of this writing can be found on his professional blog The Shadow Library.<ref>{{cite web|author=Steve_Green |url=http://shadowlibrary.blogspot.com/ |title=The Shadow Library, an online archive of reviews and essays and in his 2009 collection|publisher=Shadowlibrary.blogspot.com |date=25 July 2007 |accessdate=20 October 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn the autumn of 2019, Green co-founded Birmingham Now TV with Des Tong, Gary James and Chrissie Harper. The first episode of the magazine show 'Birmingham Now' was posted online on 25 November 2019.\n\n==Related activities==\nGreen joined the [[Birmingham Science Fiction Group]] in February 1977<ref>{{cite web|url=http://efanzines.com/Apparatchik/69-green.html |title=\"Fannish Memory Syndrome\" column in ''Apparatchik #69'' (1996): \"I first crossed paths with the Brum Group back in February 1977, when it was just six years old and arguably at the height of its powers; the guest that month was Brian Aldiss, with Chris Priest and Bob Shaw scheduled for March and April, and the group was about to run its sixth Novacon.\" |publisher=Efanzines.com |date=1 November 1996 |accessdate=20 October 2011}}</ref> and has held several posts with that organisation, including editor of its monthly newsletter. He also became a member of the [[British Science Fiction Association]], eventually taking over the clubs column (\"Life on Mars\") for its newsletter ''Matrix''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://matrix-online.net/bsfa/website/matrixonline/default.aspx |title=The British Science Fiction Association's ''Matrix'' webpage |publisher=Matrix-online.net |accessdate=20 October 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111003194414/http://matrix-online.net/bsfa/website/matrixonline/default.aspx |archive-date=3 October 2011 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mjckeh.demon.co.uk/aut0084.htm |title=BSFA index to contributors to its publications |publisher=Mjckeh.demon.co.uk |date=27 March 2011 |accessdate=20 October 2011}}</ref> Later, he collaborated with artist Kevin Clarke on a short-lived comic strip for ''Matrix'', \"The Tavern at the End of Time\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.minervatech.u-net.com/author.htm |title=Kevin Clarke's online bio, including reference to \"The Tavern at the End of Time\" |publisher=Minervatech.u-net.com |accessdate=20 October 2011}}</ref><ref>[http://sfpod.blogspot.com/2007/08/con-history-novacon-14-1984.html Illustration by Kevin Clarke for the Novacon 14 programme book, chosen by SFPod as its \"Science Fiction Picture of the Day\" on 12 September 2007; features characters from \"The Tavern at the End of Time\"]{{dead link|date=October 2011}}</ref>\n\nHe was chair of the British science fiction conventions [[Novacon|Novacon 14]] (1984),<ref>http://news.ansible.co.uk/a36.html ''Ansible #36'' (ed. Dave Langford, December 1983): \"The next Novacon [..] with S.Green as chair\"</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.ansible.co.uk/a41.html |title=''Ansible #41'' (ed. Dave Langford, December 1984): \"Novacon chair Steve Green\" |publisher=News.ansible.co.uk |accessdate=20 October 2011}}</ref> [[Novacon|Novacon 37]] (2007),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.novacon37.org.uk/ |title=Novacon 37 website \u2013 content being archived at Novacon 39 website March 2009 organised that event's film programme on several occasions [http://www.cix.co.uk/~magician/conrunner/PicturesGreen.htm \"Talking Pictures\" \u2013 article by Green on convention film programming, published in ''Conrunner #5'' (1986) and later republished in ''The Best of Conrunner'' (1987) |publisher=Novacon37.org.uk |accessdate=20 October 2011}}</ref> and Novacon 44 (2014); he also ran the \"Fan Lounge\" at Intervention, the 1997 [[Eastercon]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ansible.co.uk/writing/interven.html |title=Report by Dave Langford on the 1997 Eastercon, including references to the Fan Lounge |publisher=Ansible.co.uk |accessdate=20 October 2011}}</ref> Other roles include: [[Fantasy Amateur Press Association]] vice-president, 2005\u201307, and president-elect in 2009 (as the post was dissolved in the same ballot, Green never took office, but was briefly listed in official publications as \"president emeritus\"); administrator of the [[Nova Awards]] for British fanzines, presented annually at [[Novacon]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pdf.textfiles.com/efanzines/Nova/Nova2004.htm |title=Nova Awards update, dated November 2004, published on eFanzines |publisher=Pdf.textfiles.com |accessdate=20 October 2011}}</ref> 2002\u201309 (he reassumed the role in late 2010); former administrator of the [[Delta Film Award]], presented annually at Manchester's [[Festival of Fantastic Films (UK)|Festival of Fantastic Films]] until 2014.\n\nIn November 2008, Green announced himself as a candidate for [[TransAtlantic Fan Fund|the TransAtlantic Fan Fund]]. He won<ref>{{cite web|url=http://taff.org.uk/news/ann0904.html |title=TAFF press release issued 19 April 2009 |publisher=Taff.org.uk |date=19 April 2009 |accessdate=20 October 2011}}</ref> and subsequently attended the 2009 world sf convention, Anticipation, before travelling across Canada and the United States. He is currently working on a series of articles about his trip<ref>http://efanzines.com/Argentus/Ag09.pdf \"TAFF Notes: Prelude\", ''[[Argentus]] #9'', ed. Steven H Silver, 2009</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://efanzines.com/Beam/Beam03.pdf |title=\"LV Confidential\", ''Beam #3'', ed. Nic Farey, 2011 |accessdate=20 October 2011}}</ref> and acted as European TAFF administrator for two years, a requirement of the post.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://taff.org.uk/news/taffline-1.pdf |title=''TAFFLine #1'', 12 April 2011 |accessdate=20 October 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://taff.org.uk/news/taffline-2.pdf |title=''TAFFLine #2'', 27 April 2011 |accessdate=20 October 2011}}</ref>\n\nHe was a regular guest speaker at the Exeter University convention [[Microcon]], 2008\u201310, 2012\u201313 and 2015 (the final year it was held).\n\n[[Joel Lane]]'s 2009 short story collection ''The Terrible Changes''<ref>[http://www.exocccidente.com/terriblechanges.html Ex Oxcidente Press catalogue entry for Joel Lane's ''The Terrible Changes''] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090502175035/http://www.exocccidente.com/terriblechanges.html |date=2 May 2009 }}</ref> is dedicated to Green and to the memory of his late wife, Ann.\n\nHe is currently a director of the UK publishing imprint Rose of Eibon.\n\n==Personal life==\nGreen married fellow science fiction fan Ann Thomas (born 1961, [[Merthyr Tydfil]], Wales) in December 1983. She died in July 2008, aged 46, following a brief [[diabetes]]-related illness.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://efanzines.com/AnnGreen/ |title=Booklet produced for Ann Green's funeral, 15 August 2008 |publisher=Efanzines.com |accessdate=20 October 2011}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.ghostwords.co.uk/ Ghostwords, Steve Green's website]\n*[http://taff.org.uk/reports/taffpic2.gif Cartoon by Dave Hicks, originally published in ''Have Bag, Will Travel #2'' (1996)]\n*[http://www.roseofeibon.co.uk/ Rose of Eibon website]\n*{{isfdb name|id=Steve_Green|name=Steve Green}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Green, Steve}}\n[[Category:English magazine editors]]\n[[Category:English science fiction writers]]\n[[Category:English fantasy writers]]\n[[Category:English horror writers]]\n[[Category:English male journalists]]\n[[Category:Science fiction fans]]\n[[Category:English poets]]\n[[Category:English cartoonists]]\n[[Category:1960 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:British male poets]]\n[[Category:English male short story writers]]\n[[Category:English male novelists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=October 2011}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2011}}\n[[File:jervaulx 2005.jpg|right|250px|thumb|Ann and Steve Green at [[Jervaulx Abbey]], North Yorkshire, October 2005. Photo by Steve Green.]]\n'''Steve Green''' (born 1960, [[Solihull]], England) is a former newspaper [[reporter]] (1978\u201384) turned freelance journalist, who has also written short fiction and poetry. He is an active member of the science fiction [[science fiction fanzine|press]] and [[science fiction fandom|fan community]].\n\n==Journalism and other writings==\nSubsequent to his career as a newspaper reporter (initially on ''The Walsall Observer'', later on ''The Solihull News''), Green has contributed to such magazines as ''[[The Dark Side (magazine)|The Dark Side]]'' (for which he wrote 51 instalments of the review column \"Fanzine Focus\"), ''[[Interzone (magazine)|Interzone]]'' (interviewing the comics writer and editor [[Stan Lee]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.locusmag.com/index/t469.htm#A24911 |title=''Locus'' index for ''Interzone #59'', May 1992 |publisher=Locusmag.com |accessdate=20 October 2011}}</ref> and the author/screenwriter Peter Atkins<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.locusmag.com/index/t607.htm#A31069 |title=''Locus'' index for ''Interzone #81'', March 1994 |publisher=Locusmag.com |accessdate=20 October 2011}}</ref>), ''Fantasia'' and ''[[SFX (magazine)|SFX]]'', as well as being an occasional contributor to the 1990s [[BBC Radio 5 (former)|BBC Radio 5]] series ''The Way Out''. He wrote an online column on [[real ale]] and the British pub industry for ''[[Sunday Mercury|The Sunday Mercury]]'' in the late 2000s<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.sundaymercury.net/toby-jugg/ |title=Sunday Mercury real ale column |publisher=Blogs.sundaymercury.net |accessdate=20 October 2011}}</ref> and returned to ''The Dark Side'' as a movie reviewer in 2015.\n\nWith [[Martin Tudor (science fiction activist)|Martin Tudor]], he was also the co-editor/publisher of the science fiction journal ''[[Critical Wave]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.minervatech.u-net.com/people01.htm |title=Eulogy for the award-winning British sf author Bob Shaw, originally written by Green for ''Critical Wave'' in 1996 |publisher=Minervatech.u-net.com |accessdate=20 October 2011}}</ref> from its launch in October 1987 to its financial heat-death in mid-1996;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.ansible.co.uk/a111.html |title=''Ansible #111'' (ed. Dave Langford, October 1996): \"Sad news, indeed\" |publisher=News.ansible.co.uk |accessdate=20 October 2011}}</ref> a new, online edition was announced in September 2008,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://efanzines.com/DrinkTank/DrinkTank183.pdf |title=''The Drink Tank #183'' (ed. Chris Garcia, October 2008), announcing relaunch of ''Critical Wave'' |accessdate=20 October 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.ansible.co.uk/a255.html |title=''Ansible #255'' (ed. Dave Langford, October 2008), announcing relaunch of ''Critical Wave'' |publisher=News.ansible.co.uk |accessdate=20 October 2011}}</ref> with the same editorial team; the first issue of this new series was released in November 2008, but a second has yet to appear.\n\nIn addition to having several of his own short stories published, including \"Cracking\" in ''The Anthology of Fantasy & the Supernatural'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.locusmag.com/index/t591.htm#A30402 |title=''Locus'' index for ''The Anthology of Fantasy and the Supernatural'' (ed. Stephen Jones and David Sutton; Tiger Books, 1994) |publisher=Locusmag.com |accessdate=20 October 2011}}</ref> plus a large number of poems,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.locusmag.com/index/t477.htm#A25052 |title=''Locus'' index to ''Works #8'' (1992) |publisher=Locusmag.com |accessdate=20 October 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://fr.bookbutler.com/do/bookSearch;jsessionid=6D108A30E5288AC423214AC97A7CE7E5?pageNr=1&showMore=true&sortBy=salesrank&searchFor=1+85731+439+5&searchBy=isbn&searchIn=uk&shipTo=gb&amountIn=gbp&zip= |title=''That's Entertainment'', edited by Kerrie Pateman (Poetry Now, 1995), ISBN 1-85731-439-5 |publisher=Fr.bookbutler.com |accessdate=20 October 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://fr.bookbutler.com/do/bookSearch?showMore=true&shipTo=gb&amountIn=gbp&zip=&sortBy=salesrank&pageNr=1&searchFor=0907376150&searchBy=isbn&searchIn=uk |title=''Dreamers on the Sea of Fate'', edited by Steve Sneyd (Sol, 1999), ISBN 0-907376-15-0 |publisher=Fr.bookbutler.com |accessdate=20 October 2011}}</ref> Green appears as a supporting character in both [[David Langford]]'s comic novel ''The Leaky Establishment''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ansible.co.uk/books/leaky2.jpg |title=Cover of the 1985 paperback edition of ''The Leaky Establishment''; the character named for Green can be seen emerging from the pub, notebook in hand |accessdate=20 October 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927025101/http://www.ansible.co.uk/books/leaky2.jpg |archive-date=27 September 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and [[Joel Lane]]'s novella ''The Witnesses Are Gone''<ref>[http://store.pspublishing.co.uk/acatalog/info_417.html PS Publishing catalogue entry for ''The Witnesses Are Gone'' by Joel Lane]</ref> (the latter also features his late wife, Ann Green).\n\nDuring the mid-1990s, Green was a regular columnist for both the [[Seattle]] [[freesheet]] ''Mansplat!''<ref>http://www.mansplat.com/ ''Mansplat!'' website, including partial index</ref> and the focal point American [[fanzine]] ''Apparatchik'' (examples:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://efanzines.com/Apparatchik/65-green.html |title=\"Fannish Memory Syndrome\" column in ''Apparatchik #65'', 8 August 1996 |publisher=Efanzines.com |date=8 August 1996 |accessdate=20 October 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://efanzines.com/Apparatchik/66-green.html |title=\"Fannish Memory Syndrome\" column in ''Apparatchik #66'', 29 August 1996 |publisher=Efanzines.com |date=29 August 1996 |accessdate=20 October 2011}}</ref><ref>[http://efanzines.com/Apparatchik/71-green.htm \"Fannish Memory Syndrome]\" column in ''Apparatchik #71'', 13 December 1996]{{dead link|date=October 2011}}</ref>). His ''Apparatchik'' column, \"Fannish Memory Syndrome\", was relaunched in the [[Hugo Award for Best Amateur Magazine|Hugo Award]]-nominated US fanzine ''The Drink Tank''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://efanzines.com/DrinkTank/ |title=Bill Burns' eFanzines index of links to downloadable issues of 'The Drink Tank' |publisher=Efanzines.com |date=7 July 2005 |accessdate=20 October 2011}}</ref> in September 2007.<ref>http://efanzines.com/DrinkTank/DrinkTank143.pdf</ref> Selected examples of this writing can be found on his professional blog The Shadow Library.<ref>{{cite web|author=Steve_Green |url=http://shadowlibrary.blogspot.com/ |title=The Shadow Library, an online archive of reviews and essays and in his 2009 collection|publisher=Shadowlibrary.blogspot.com |date=25 July 2007 |accessdate=20 October 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn the autumn of 2019, Green co-founded Birmingham Now TV with Des Tong, Gary James and Chrissie Harper. The first episode of the magazine show 'Birmingham Now' was posted online on 25 November 2019.\n\n==Related activities==\nGreen joined the [[Birmingham Science Fiction Group]] in February 1977<ref>{{cite web|url=http://efanzines.com/Apparatchik/69-green.html |title=\"Fannish Memory Syndrome\" column in ''Apparatchik #69'' (1996): \"I first crossed paths with the Brum Group back in February 1977, when it was just six years old and arguably at the height of its powers; the guest that month was Brian Aldiss, with Chris Priest and Bob Shaw scheduled for March and April, and the group was about to run its sixth Novacon.\" |publisher=Efanzines.com |date=1 November 1996 |accessdate=20 October 2011}}</ref> and has held several posts with that organisation, including editor of its monthly newsletter. He also became a member of the [[British Science Fiction Association]], eventually taking over the clubs column (\"Life on Mars\") for its newsletter ''Matrix''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://matrix-online.net/bsfa/website/matrixonline/default.aspx |title=The British Science Fiction Association's ''Matrix'' webpage |publisher=Matrix-online.net |accessdate=20 October 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111003194414/http://matrix-online.net/bsfa/website/matrixonline/default.aspx |archive-date=3 October 2011 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mjckeh.demon.co.uk/aut0084.htm |title=BSFA index to contributors to its publications |publisher=Mjckeh.demon.co.uk |date=27 March 2011 |accessdate=20 October 2011}}</ref> Later, he collaborated with artist Kevin Clarke on a short-lived comic strip for ''Matrix'', \"The Tavern at the End of Time\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.minervatech.u-net.com/author.htm |title=Kevin Clarke's online bio, including reference to \"The Tavern at the End of Time\" |publisher=Minervatech.u-net.com |accessdate=20 October 2011}}</ref><ref>[http://sfpod.blogspot.com/2007/08/con-history-novacon-14-1984.html Illustration by Kevin Clarke for the Novacon 14 programme book, chosen by SFPod as its \"Science Fiction Picture of the Day\" on 12 September 2007; features characters from \"The Tavern at the End of Time\"]{{dead link|date=October 2011}}</ref>\n\nHe was chair of the British science fiction conventions [[Novacon|Novacon 14]] (1984),<ref>http://news.ansible.co.uk/a36.html ''Ansible #36'' (ed. Dave Langford, December 1983): \"The next Novacon [..] with S.Green as chair\"</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.ansible.co.uk/a41.html |title=''Ansible #41'' (ed. Dave Langford, December 1984): \"Novacon chair Steve Green\" |publisher=News.ansible.co.uk |accessdate=20 October 2011}}</ref> [[Novacon|Novacon 37]] (2007),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.novacon37.org.uk/ |title=Novacon 37 website \u2013 content being archived at Novacon 39 website March 2009 organised that event's film programme on several occasions [http://www.cix.co.uk/~magician/conrunner/PicturesGreen.htm \"Talking Pictures\" \u2013 article by Green on convention film programming, published in ''Conrunner #5'' (1986) and later republished in ''The Best of Conrunner'' (1987) |publisher=Novacon37.org.uk |accessdate=20 October 2011}}</ref> and Novacon 44 (2014); he also ran the \"Fan Lounge\" at Intervention, the 1997 [[Eastercon]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ansible.co.uk/writing/interven.html |title=Report by Dave Langford on the 1997 Eastercon, including references to the Fan Lounge |publisher=Ansible.co.uk |accessdate=20 October 2011}}</ref> Other roles include: [[Fantasy Amateur Press Association]] vice-president, 2005\u201307, and president-elect in 2009 (as the post was dissolved in the same ballot, Green never took office, but was briefly listed in official publications as \"president emeritus\"); administrator of the [[Nova Awards]] for British fanzines, presented annually at [[Novacon]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pdf.textfiles.com/efanzines/Nova/Nova2004.htm |title=Nova Awards update, dated November 2004, published on eFanzines |publisher=Pdf.textfiles.com |accessdate=20 October 2011}}</ref> 2002\u201309 (he reassumed the role in late 2010); former administrator of the [[Delta Film Award]], presented annually at Manchester's [[Festival of Fantastic Films (UK)|Festival of Fantastic Films]] until 2014.\n\nIn November 2008, Green announced himself as a candidate for [[TransAtlantic Fan Fund|the TransAtlantic Fan Fund]]. He won<ref>{{cite web|url=http://taff.org.uk/news/ann0904.html |title=TAFF press release issued 19 April 2009 |publisher=Taff.org.uk |date=19 April 2009 |accessdate=20 October 2011}}</ref> and subsequently attended the 2009 world sf convention, Anticipation, before travelling across Canada and the United States. He is currently working on a series of articles about his trip<ref>http://efanzines.com/Argentus/Ag09.pdf \"TAFF Notes: Prelude\", ''[[Argentus]] #9'', ed. Steven H Silver, 2009</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://efanzines.com/Beam/Beam03.pdf |title=\"LV Confidential\", ''Beam #3'', ed. Nic Farey, 2011 |accessdate=20 October 2011}}</ref> and acted as European TAFF administrator for two years, a requirement of the post.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://taff.org.uk/news/taffline-1.pdf |title=''TAFFLine #1'', 12 April 2011 |accessdate=20 October 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://taff.org.uk/news/taffline-2.pdf |title=''TAFFLine #2'', 27 April 2011 |accessdate=20 October 2011}}</ref>\n\nHe was a regular guest speaker at the Exeter University convention [[Microcon]], 2008\u201310, 2012\u201313 and 2015 (the final year it was held).\n\n[[Joel Lane]]'s 2009 short story collection ''The Terrible Changes''<ref>[http://www.exocccidente.com/terriblechanges.html Ex Oxcidente Press catalogue entry for Joel Lane's ''The Terrible Changes''] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090502175035/http://www.exocccidente.com/terriblechanges.html |date=2 May 2009 }}</ref> is dedicated to Green and to the memory of his late wife, Ann.\n\nHe is currently a director of the UK publishing imprint Rose of Eibon.\n\n==Personal life==\nGreen married fellow science fiction fan Ann Thomas (born 1961, [[Merthyr Tydfil]], Wales) in December 1983. She died in July 2008, aged 46, following a brief [[diabetes]]-related illness.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://efanzines.com/AnnGreen/ |title=Booklet produced for Ann Green's funeral, 15 August 2008 |publisher=Efanzines.com |accessdate=20 October 2011}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.ghostwords.co.uk/ Ghostwords, Steve Green's website]\n*[http://taff.org.uk/reports/taffpic2.gif Cartoon by Dave Hicks, originally published in ''Have Bag, Will Travel #2'' (1996)]\n*[http://www.roseofeibon.co.uk/ Rose of Eibon website]\n*{{isfdb name|id=Steve_Green|name=Steve Green}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Green, Steve}}\n[[Category:English magazine editors]]\n[[Category:English science fiction writers]]\n[[Category:English fantasy writers]]\n[[Category:English horror writers]]\n[[Category:English male journalists]]\n[[Category:Science fiction fans]]\n[[Category:English poets]]\n[[Category:English cartoonists]]\n[[Category:1960 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:British male poets]]\n[[Category:English male short story writers]]\n[[Category:English male novelists]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Steve_Green_(journalist)"}
{"title_page": "2016 Super Rugby season", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox Super Rugby season\n| name                = 2016 Super Rugby season\n| image               = \n| imagesize           = \n| caption             = \n| countries           = [[Argentina]] (1 team) <br/> [[Australia]] (5 teams) <br/> [[Japan]] (1 team) <br/> [[New Zealand]] (5 teams) <br/> [[South Africa]] (6 teams)\n| tournament format   = [[Round-robin tournament|Round-robin]] and [[Single-elimination tournament|knockout]]\n| champions           = [[Hurricanes (rugby union)|Hurricanes]]\n| count               = 1\n| matches             = 142\n| attendance          = \n| tries               = 910\n| top point scorer    = [[Beauden Barrett]] (223)\n| top try scorer      = [[Israel Folau]] (11)\n| website             = [http://www.sanzarrugby.com/superrugby Official site]\n| previous year       = 2015\n| previous tournament = 2015 Super Rugby season\n| next year           = 2017\n| next tournament     = 2017 Super Rugby season\n}}\n\nThe '''2016 Super Rugby season''' was the 21st season of [[Super Rugby]] and the first season featuring an expanded 18-team format. It was also the first season that teams outside [[Australia]], [[New Zealand]] and [[South Africa]] featured, with the Jaguares from [[Argentina]] and the Sunwolves from [[Japan]] taking part. This season also saw the return of the Kings, who competed just once before, in the [[2013 Super Rugby season]].<ref name=\"Japan given the nod for Super Rugby\">{{cite web | url=http://www.sanzarrugby.com/superrugby/news/japan-given-the-nod-for-super-rugby/ | title=Japan given the nod for Super Rugby | publisher=SANZAAR | date=24 October 2014 | accessdate=24 October 2014}}</ref>\n<!--For sponsorship reasons, this competition is known as [[Suncorp Group#Business interests|Asteron Life]] Super Rugby in Australia, [[Investec Bank|Investec]] Super Rugby in New Zealand and [[Vodacom]] Super Rugby in South Africa. -->The round-robin games took place every weekend from 26 February to 16 July 2016 (with a break for international matches during June), followed by the finals series at the end of July and culminating in the final on 6 August.\n\nThe [[Hurricanes (rugby union)|Hurricanes]] won their first championship after repeating their efforts of 2015 by finishing first in the regular season and hosting the final at [[Westpac Stadium]], but this time they won, beating the [[Lions (Super Rugby)|Lions]] 20\u20133. Unlike 2015, where the [[Hurricanes (rugby union)|Hurricanes]] looked likely to finish the regular season first with a number of rounds to go, they were sitting in seventh going into the final week of the regular season and while guaranteed a play-off spot, they required a number of upset results to elevate them to first. In particular the [[Lions (Super Rugby)|Lions]] losing to the Jaguares and scoring no match points after sending an under-strength side to Argentina, thereby losing their chance to host the final.\n\n==Competition format==\n\nThe 18 teams were grouped geographically in two regional groups, each consisting of two conferences: the Australasian Group, with five teams in the Australian Conference and five teams in the New Zealand Conference and the South African Group, with six South African teams, one Argentinean team and one Japanese team split into a four-team Africa 1 Conference and a four-team Africa 2 Conference.<ref name=\"Outline of the Super Rugby competition structure\">{{cite web | url=http://files.allblacks.com/comms/new-era-super-rugby/Outline-%20Super-Rugby-Comp-Structure-infographic.pdf | title=Outline of the Super Rugby competition structure | publisher=All Blacks | date=1 May 2014 | accessdate=1 May 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn the group stages, there were 17 rounds of matches, where each team played 15 matches and had two rounds of byes for a total of 135 matches.\n\nTeams played six intra-conference matches; in the four-team African Conferences, each team played the other three teams in their conference at home and away, while in the five-team Australasian Conferences, each team played two teams home and away and once against the other two teams (one at home and one away). The other nine matches were a single round of matches against each team in the other conference in their group, as well as against each team from one of the conferences in the other group. For 2016, the teams in Africa 1 played the teams in the Australian Conference, while the teams in Africa 2 played the teams in the New Zealand Conference.\n\nThe top team in each of the four conferences automatically qualified to the Quarter Finals. The next top three teams in the Australasian Group and the next top team in the South African group also qualified to the Quarter Finals as wildcards. The conference winners were seeded #1 to #4 for the Quarter Finals, in order of log points gained during the group stages, while the wildcards were seeded as #5 to #8 in order of log points gained during the group stages.\n\nIn the Quarter Finals, the conference winners hosted the first round of the finals, with the highest-seeded conference winner hosting the fourth-seeded wildcard entry, the second-seeded conference winner hosting the third-seeded wildcard entry, the third-seeded conference winner hosting the second-seeded wildcard entry and the fourth-seeded conference winner hosting the top-seed wildcard entry.\n\nThe Quarter Final winners progressed to the Semi-Finals, where the highest seed to reach the Semi-Finals hosted the lowest seed and the second-seeded semi-finalist hosted the third-seeded team.\n\nThe winners of the Semi-Finals progressed to the Final, at the venue of the highest-seeded team.\n\n==Standings==\n{{2016 Super Rugby standings}}\n\n==Matches==\n{{main|List of 2016 Super Rugby matches}}\n\nThe fixtures for the 2016 Super Rugby competition were released on 28 September 2015:<ref name=\"Draw released for new era of Super Rugby\">{{cite press release | url=http://www.sanzarrugby.com/superrugby/news/draw-released-for-new-era-of-super-rugby/ | title=Draw released for new era of Super Rugby | publisher=SANZAAR | date=28 September 2015 | accessdate=28 September 2015}}</ref> The following matches were played during the regular season:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable collapsible\" style=\"text-align:center; width:80%\"\n|-\n! colspan=100% | Team Progression \u2013 Australasian Group\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:left; width:20%;\" | Team\n! style=\"width:4%;\" | R1\n! style=\"width:4%;\" | R2\n! style=\"width:4%;\" | R3\n! style=\"width:4%;\" | R4\n! style=\"width:4%;\" | R5\n! style=\"width:4%;\" | R6\n! style=\"width:4%;\" | R7\n! style=\"width:4%;\" | R8\n! style=\"width:4%;\" | R9\n! style=\"width:4%;\" | R10\n! style=\"width:4%;\" | R11\n! style=\"width:4%;\" | R12\n! style=\"width:4%;\" | R13\n! style=\"width:4%;\" | R14\n! style=\"width:4%;\" | R15\n! style=\"width:4%;\" | R16\n! style=\"width:4%;\" | R17\n! style=\"width:4%;\" | QF\n! style=\"width:4%;\" | SF\n! style=\"width:4%;\" | Final\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | Hurricanes\n| <!--Round 1 --> style=\"background:#FFCCCC;\" | 0 <br/> <small>(10th)</small>\n| <!--Round 2 --> style=\"background:#FFCCCC;\" | 1 <br/> <small>(9th)</small>\n| <!--Round 3 --> style=\"background:#E8FFD8;\" | 5 <br/> <small>(9th)</small>\n| <!--Round 4 --> style=\"background:#E8FFD8;\" | 10 <br/> <small>(6th)</small>\n| <!--Round 5 --> style=\"background:#E8FFD8;\" | 15 <br/> <small>(4th)</small>\n| <!--Round 6 --> style=\"background:#ECECEC;\" | 15 <br/> <small>(6th)</small>\n| <!--Round 7 --> style=\"background:#E8FFD8;\" | 20 <br/> <small>(5th)</small>\n| <!--Round 8 --> style=\"background:#E8FFD8;\" | 25 <br/> <small>(4th)</small>\n| <!--Round 9 --> style=\"background:#FFCCCC;\" | 26 <br/> <small>(4th)</small>\n| <!--Round 10--> style=\"background:#E8FFD8;\" | 31 <br/> <small>(4th)</small>\n| <!--Round 11--> style=\"background:#FFCCCC;\" | 31 <br/> <small>(5th)</small>\n| <!--Round 12--